365	S	anonimo	2024-09-23 17:08:45	2024-11-22 07:10:25	78	2023-09-27 00:00:00	SV02 Flamenco 3 days	Art, Dance & Flamenco	art-dance--flamenco	<strong><span style=\\"color: #ff008c;\\">The essence of flamenco music and dance in Seville</span></strong>\\r\\n\\r\\nImmerse yourself in the captivating world of flamenco in Sevilla as you explore its most iconic corners. From historic neighborhoods to the most authentic tablao venues, this experience will take you to the heart of flamenco music and dance. Plus, savor authentic local cuisine at spots frequented by flamenco enthusiasts. Let the passion, music, and flavors of Sevilla sweep you away.	1	pexels-mark-neal-3365379.jpg	1	<p>For your arrival day, I recommend starting in the Macarena area, visiting the arch and the <strong><a style=\\"color: #f41b8c; text-decoration: underline;\\" href=\\"#basilica\\">Basilica</a></strong>, as well as the brotherhood museum. Also, explore <strong><a style=\\"color: #f41b8c; text-decoration: underline;\\" href=\\"#alamedadehercules\\">Alameda de Hércules</a></strong>, which was the heart of bohemian flamenco during much of the 20th century. In Alameda, you can visit the <strong><a style=\\"color: #f41b8c; text-decoration: underline;\\" href=\\"#monumenttoniñadelospeines\\">Monument to La Niña de los Peines</a></strong> (Pastora Pavón), one of the greatest flamenco singers of all time, and the guitarist Manolo Caracol. Later, take the opportunity to visit <strong><a style=\\"color: #f41b8c; text-decoration: underline;\\" href=\\"#monumentalensembleofsaintlouisofthefrench\\">Monumental Ensemble of Saint Louis of the French</a></strong> (until 5 PM), the grand jewel of Seville?s Baroque architecture, which is used every year as a stage in the Flamenco Bienal, a unique spectacle.</p><p>If you?re interested in learning some flamenco basics like rhythm and beats, there are 1-hour courses available from Monday to Friday until 8 PM at <strong><a style=\\"color: #f41b8c; text-decoration: underline;\\" href=\\"#tallerflamencosevilla\\">Taller Flamenco Sevilla</a></strong>. I?ll provide the information for booking in the points of interest.</p><p>For dinner, I recommend going to <strong><a style=\\"color: #f41b8c; text-decoration: underline;\\" href=\\"#penaculturalflamencatorresmacarena\\">Peña Cultural Flamenca Torres Macarena</a></strong>, an intimate flamenco center with live performances in its courtyard, where tapas and cold beer are served along with the show. They also have a charming terrace in a very Sevillian atmosphere (closed on Saturdays, Mondays, and Tuesdays; usually the show starts after 8 PM). If you prefer a quieter option, try <strong><a style=\\"color: #f41b8c; text-decoration: underline;\\" href=\\"#alaljiberestaurant\\">Restaurant Al Aljibe</a></strong> right in the heart of Alameda.</p><p>If you?re looking for a more immersive experience, one option I recommend for dining today or any other day is to try <strong><a style=\\"color: #f41b8c; text-decoration: underline;\\" href=\\"#sazon\\">SAZÓN The Folk Cook</a></strong>, SAZON is the world\\ s first platform to provide Spanish food homely prepared by locals at their own houses, where you would taste it in complete privacy.</p>                	<p>Today, I won?t reveal anything new, but I do highly recommend visiting the famous <strong><a style=\\"color: #f41b8c; text-decoration: underline;\\" href=\\"#plazadeespana\\">Plaza de España</a></strong>. It?s a must-see where you can also find street flamenco performances in the square or under some of the arches, which are worth a look. Since you?re in the area, a stroll through Maria Luisa Park is a must. Afterward, head to the Santa Cruz neighborhood, a place where the duende resides and art permeates every corner. It undeniably has a special atmosphere that?s hard to put into words. Its narrow streets and flamenco music make it a place with a unique charm. Here, you can wander through the narrow streets of the Jewish quarter and its orange tree patios like <strong><a style=\\"color: #f41b8c; text-decoration: underline;\\" href=\\"#plazadedonaelvira\\">Plaza de Doña Elvira</a></strong>. Or <strong><a style=\\"color: #f41b8c; text-decoration: underline;\\" href=\\"#calleagua\\">Calle Agua</a></strong> :)</p><p>I recommend having lunch at <strong><a style=\\"color: #f41b8c; text-decoration: underline;\\" href=\\"#lasteresas\\">Las Teresas</a></strong> and trying the daily stew along with a delicious ham tapa. After lunch, you can stroll down Calle Cuna and Sierpes. In the vicinity of Plaza del Salvador, you?ll find numerous workshops for flamenco dresses, a fashion unique to the world (you can check out some stores like Sonibel or Carmen if you?re interested).</p><p>And of course, don?t forget to visit the <strong><a style=\\"color: #f41b8c; text-decoration: underline;\\" href=\\"#flamencodancemuseum\\">Flamenco Dance Museum</a></strong>, founded by the famous dancer Cristina Hoyos? absolutely essential! If you?re looking for a tablao in this area, I recommend <strong><a style=\\"color: #f41b8c; text-decoration: underline;\\" href=\\"#lacasadelflamenco\\">La Casa del Flamenco</a></strong>, with several shows each evening and a very comprehensive performance.</p><p>For dinner, you can go to <strong><a style=\\"color: #f41b8c; text-decoration: underline;\\" href=\\"#loscoloniales\\">Los Coloniales</a></strong>, a typical Andalusian tavern with painted tiles. The whisky-marinated pork tenderloin is delicious! If you?d like to have a drink afterwards, you can go to <strong><a style=\\"color: #f41b8c; text-decoration: underline;\\" href=\\"#lacarboneria\\">La Carbonería</a></strong>.</p>                	<p>Today we can start the morning with a walk along the river, passing by the Torre del Oro and <strong><a style=\\"color: #f41b8c; text-decoration: underline;\\" href=\\"#plazadetorosdelamaestranza\\">La Maestranza</a></strong> (with the statue of Curro Romero), until we reach the <strong><a style=\\"color: #f41b8c; text-decoration: underline;\\" href=\\"#puentedetriana\\">Triana Bridge</a></strong>, where, once crossed, we find ourselves in the historic heart of flamenco: the Triana neighborhood :)</p><p>Crossing the Triana Bridge offers spectacular views. In Plaza del Altozano, you?ll find a sculpture of a woman with a guitar facing the Carmen Chapel (<strong><a style=\\"color: #f41b8c; text-decoration: underline;\\" href=\\"#monumentotrianaalarteflamenco\\">monument ?Triana to Flamenco Art?</a></strong> created by Jesús Gavira), which is a true symbol of Triana. Don?t forget to visit the <strong><a style=\\"color: #f41b8c; text-decoration: underline;\\" href=\\"#mercadodetriana\\">Triana Market</a></strong>, where there are plenty of stalls of all kinds in case you want to have a snack or enjoy a gin and tonic at Kiosko Juan Carlos (stall 37). If you haven?t eaten at the market, another option is <strong><a style=\\"color: #f41b8c; text-decoration: underline;\\" href=\\"#lasgolondrinaspagesdelcorro\\">Las Golondrinas Pagés del Corro</a></strong>.</p><p>To end the afternoon, if you haven?t yet been to a tablao, you have the <strong><a style=\\"color: #f41b8c; text-decoration: underline;\\" href=\\"#teatroflamencotriana\\">Teatro Flamenco Triana</a></strong> here, a highly recommended show. If you?re a fan of Holy Week, in Triana you have two chapels that are a must-visit: the <strong><a style=\\"color: #f41b8c; text-decoration: underline;\\" href=\\"#capilladelosmarineros\\">Capilla de los Marineros</a></strong> with the highly venerated image of the Esperanza de Triana, and that of the <strong><a style=\\"color: #f41b8c; text-decoration: underline;\\" href=\\"#hermandaddelaestrella\\">Brotherhood of La Estrella</a></strong> on Calle San Jacinto.</p><p>For dinner in Triana, I recommend <strong><a style=\\"color: #f41b8c; text-decoration: underline;\\" href=\\"#barbistec\\">Bar Bistec</a></strong> in Plaza de Santa Ana. If you want another option closer to the center, crossing the bridge behind La Maestranza, you?ll find <strong><a style=\\"color: #f41b8c; text-decoration: underline;\\" href=\\"#tabernacasasarmiento\\">Taberna Casa Sarmiento</a></strong> with photos of the master Camarón de la Isla. If you?d like to have a drink at night, on Calle Betis you have <strong><a style=\\"color: #f41b8c; text-decoration: underline;\\" href=\\"#lonuestro\\">Lo Nuestro</a></strong> or <strong><a style=\\"color: #f41b8c; text-decoration: underline;\\" href=\\"#losmartinezpremium\\">Los Martínez Premium</a></strong>.</p><p>Enjoy!</p>\t\t	365	pexels-mark-neal-3365379.jpg	1087	14.9	15.65	70069.40	S	en	7,2,25,12,1,11,23,13,24,16,14,21,27,15,28,20,3,4,19,6,10,9,17,18,8,26,5,22	&lt;iframe src=\\"https://www.google.com/maps/d/u/2/embed?mid=1OiOYYUb_7IWJ2WpVdKS3FpKF_7Bwd-c&ehbc=2E312F&noprof=1\\" width=\\"640\\" height=\\"480\\"&gt;	prod_QuHsubYYtfNpM7	price_1Q2TIXAFILSEnUZXAGkCtnDL	1	S	S	The essence of flamenco music and dance in Seville	\N	\N	Art, Dance & Flamenco	prod_QuosrQPhBUkKTD	price_1Q2zEyAFILSEnUZX54sE353B		https://buy.stripe.com/test_3cs5ntcZvaOa3sI3h2		plink_1Q3B9nAFILSEnUZXw3jAFbnd	3Dias	2	N
366	S	anonimo	2024-09-23 17:08:59	2024-11-22 07:10:25	79	2023-09-28 00:00:00	SV01 Cofrade 3 days	Dive into the Cofrade Atmosphere	dive-into-the-cofrade-atmosphere	<strong><span style=\\"color: #ff008c;\\">Culture, Tapas and Devotion in Seville</span></strong>\\r\\n\\r\\nExplore Seville\\ s vibrant cofrade culture as you visit its most iconic spots. From La Macarena church to the evocative Capilla de los Marineros in Triana, this itinerary immerses you in the devotion and fervor that define the city. Plus, savor authentic local cuisine at places frequented by Seville\\ s cofrades. This unique experience will connect you with Seville\\ s history, tradition, culture, and flavors, taking you to the essence of this unforgettable city.	2	semana-santa-sevilla-1.jpg	1	<p>To start, there?s nothing better than a stroll to get to know <a href=\\"#basilicadelamacarena\\"><strong>La Macarena church</strong></a> and visit its brotherhood museum to see its most relevant pieces and learn about their history. In the Macarena arch area, you?ll find some bars decorated with Semana Santa images and terraces for coffee, a beer, or a tapa (like <a href=\\"#baresperanza\\"><strong>Bar Esperanza</strong></a> or <a href=\\"#barrosadesangil\\"><strong>Bar Rosa de San Gil</strong></a> that smells like incense).</p>\\r\\n\\r\\n<p>For lunch, you can?t miss <a href=\\"#bodeguitaromeroymejias\\"><strong>Bodeguita Romero & Mejias</strong> </a>,a must-visit for those of us who enjoy the Semana Santa spirit any time of the year. If you?re looking for a more immersive experience, one option I recommend for dining today or any other day is to try <strong><a href=\\"#sazon\\">SAZÓN The Folk Cook</a></strong>, SAZON is the world\\ s first platform to provide Spanish food homely prepared by locals at their own houses, where you would taste it in complete privacy.</p>\\r\\n\\r\\n<p>In the afternoon, we can continue in the Alameda area, visit the <strong><a href=\\"#iglesiagranpoder\\">basilica of El Gran Poder</a></strong>, and the <a href=\\"#parroquiasanlorenzomartir\\"><strong>Parish of San Lorenzo Mártir </strong></a>to admire the images of the Dulce Nombre brotherhood.</p>\\r\\n\\r\\n<p>For dinner, a typical place to try the local cuisine is <a href=\\"#bodegasanlorenzo\\"><strong>La bodega San Lorenzo  </strong></a>a place with good tapas and a nice atmosphere. Another option is <a href=\\"#casaricardo\\"><strong>Bar Casa Ricardo</strong></a>, a restaurant with a wide variety of tapas and dishes very close to El Gran Poder.</p>\\r\\n\\r\\n<p>If you feel like having a drink at night, you have the vibrant Alameda area nearby, full of terraces and a great atmosphere. You can have a drink on the terrace of <a href=\\"#pubritual\\"><strong>Pub Ritual</strong></a> or in <a href=\\"#cafecentral\\"><strong>café Central</strong></a> if you prefer something more bohemian and neighborhood-like.</p>\\r\\n	<p>This morning, head to the <a href=\\"#magdalena\\"><strong>Parish of Santa María Magdalena</strong></a>. In this area, you can have churros with chocolate or a famous mollete with ham (a very typical Andalusian breakfast) at <strong><a href=\\"#donacarmen\\">bar </a></strong><strong>Doña Carmen. </strong></p>\\r\\n\\r\\n<p>Since you?re in the center, other lesser-known but worth-visiting parishes in the Metropol Parasol area are <a href=\\"#sanpedroapostol\\"><strong>San Pedro Apóstol</strong></a>, <a href=\\"#santacatalina\\"><strong>Santa Catalina</strong></a>, or the <a href=\\"#buensuceso\\"><strong>church of El Buen Suceso</strong></a>. If you want to have a snack in the area with a completely Semana Santa atmosphere, don?t miss going to <a href=\\"#losclaveles\\"><strong>Los Claveles</strong></a> or <a href=\\"#elrinconcillo\\"><strong>El Rinconcillo</strong></a>.</p>\\r\\n\\r\\n<p>To continue the afternoon, take a walk through the Santa Cruz neighborhood, it undoubtedly has a special atmosphere that can?t be described. Its narrow streets and street flamenco make it a place with a lot of charm. Walk through its narrow streets of the Jewish quarter and its orange tree patios like <a href=\\"#plazadonaelvira\\"><strong>Plaza de doña Elvira</strong></a> or<a href=\\"#calleverde\\"><strong> la </strong></a><strong><a href=\\"#calleverde\\">calle Verde </a>,</strong> the narrowest street in Sevilla :)</p>\\r\\n\\r\\n<p>Nearby, I recommend visiting the <a href=\\"#venerables\\"><strong>Hospital de los Venerables</strong></a> which houses a library and works by Velázquez. Another option, if it?s from Monday to Thursday (it closes from Friday to Sunday), is the beautiful <a href=\\"#santamarialablanca\\"><strong>Church of Santa María la Blanca</strong></a>. And for a late afternoon outing, go up to the rooftop of the <a href=\\"#hotelemecatedral\\"><strong>Hotel EME Catedral</strong></a>, its views of Sevilla are on another level.</p>\\r\\n\\r\\n<p>Since you?re in the area of the cathedral, don?t miss <a href=\\"#plazadeelsalvador\\"><strong>Plaza de el Salvador</strong></a> and its church, the hidden <a href=\\"#plazadelcabildo\\"><strong>plaza del Cabildo</strong></a>, for dinner time, you have <a href=\\"#lascolumnas\\"><strong>Bar Santa Cruz ?Las Columnas?</strong></a>. If you fancy something more chic and quiet, not far away you have the restaurant <strong><a href=\\"#lobolopez\\">Lobo López</a>, one of my favorites.</strong></p>\\r\\n	<p>Today is a great day for a stroll to the <a href=\\"#puentedetriana\\"><strong>puente de Triana</strong></a> and cross over to visit the <a href=\\"#capilladelosmarineros\\"><strong>Capilla de los Marineros</strong></a>. There?s also a chapel right on the bridge (next to the entrance to the San Jorge Castle and the Triana Market) where you can stop and take some great photos. If you feel like having breakfast in the area, you can go to <a href=\\"#labaronesa\\"><strong>La Baronesa</strong></a>. </p>\\r\\n\\r\\n<p>And don?t forget to visit the <a href=\\"#cristoexpiracion\\"><strong>Basílica del Stmo. Cristo de la Expiración</strong></a> to admire the images of the famous El Cachorro brotherhood.</p>\\r\\n\\r\\n<p>If you want to have some tapas you can go to <strong><a href=\\"#akela\\">Akela</a></strong>, a typical bar where people gather to have beers and some tapas at noon. An option with a terrace and tables is <a href=\\"#barbistec\\"><strong>bar bistec </strong></a>right in the middle of Plazuela Santa Ana. </p>\\r\\n\\r\\n<p>If you want an indoor option, in the <a href=\\"#mercadodetriana\\"><strong>Triana Market</strong>,</a> you can take the opportunity to stop at any of the stalls to try paella or even sushi. You should go even if it?s just for a stroll.</p>\\r\\n\\r\\n<p>To relax after eating, if you feel like having some gin and tonics, there?s a stall in the market with all kinds of gins to taste called Donde Juan Carlos (stall 37). If you fancy a drink on a terrace, you have the terrace of the <a href=\\"#hotelzenit\\"><strong>Zenit hotel</strong></a>. And if you fancy something sweet after eating, ice cream at <a href=\\"#marialimones\\"><strong>María Limones Triana</strong></a>.</p>\\r\\n\\r\\n<p>Enjoy!</p>\\r\\n	366	semana-santa-sevilla-1.jpg	1088,1089,1090,1091,1092,1093,1094,1095,1096,1097,1098,1099	14.9	15.65	70069.40	S	en	61,25,41,30,31,12,1,60,36,32,39,48,23,37,46,65,49,51,64,43,50,44,34,42,59,54,55,45,20,40,35,10,53,38,18,8	&lt;iframe src=\\"https://www.google.com/maps/d/u/2/embed?mid=1nZtJ_kXtxcNfq10UDcNH0-fB6WkgPK0&ehbc=2E312F&noprof=1\\" width=\\"640\\" height=\\"480\\"&gt;	prod_QuHtwUdPKIRdcA	price_1Q2TJmAFILSEnUZXxKKhu17w	1	S	N	Culture, Tapas and Devotion in Seville	\N	\N	Dive into the Cofrade Atmosphere	prod_QuossshPB2XbDr	price_1Q2zEyAFILSEnUZXj5t7mz1F		https://buy.stripe.com/test_14kaHN7Fb4pM6EU7xj		plink_1Q3B9oAFILSEnUZXMUrnYXxR	3Dias	3	N
367	S	anonimo	2024-09-23 17:09:10	2024-11-22 07:10:25	4750	2023-09-29 00:00:00	SV05 Gourmet & Relax 3 days	Gourmet & Relax	gourmet--relax	<strong><span style=\\"color: #ff008c;\\">Take a break and treat yourself with your partner in Seville</span></strong>\\r\\n\\r\\nSet off on a journey through Seville where history and culture intertwine. Explore the city, unwind at spas, savor local cuisine, and enjoy magical sunsets while cruising the Guadalquivir River. Immerse yourself in a unique experience full of discoveries and flavors in this charming city.	3	pexels-cottonbro-studio-3997983.jpg	1	<p>We start our first day by leisurely enjoying a coffee and breakfast at <a href=\\"#mokambo\\"><strong>Mokambo café</strong></a>. This café offers healthy breakfasts and brunches with fresh, organic products ? a true celebration of real food. The owners? hospitality is excellent, and you can tell they prepare everything with care.</p><p>From here, we head to our first relaxation experience in the city.</p><ul><li><a href=\\"#aire\\"><strong>Aire de Sevilla Arab Baths</strong></a>: The place is stunning. They offer a thermal circuit with various massage options, treatments, and experiences, both for individuals and couples. The terrace with a jacuzzi is absolutely enchanting. The service is fantastic, and I always leave feeling incredibly relaxed.</li></ul><p>Once thoroughly relaxed at the spa, I recommend some gourmet spots to savor the city?s cuisine:</p><ul><li><a href=\\"#zelai\\"><strong>Zelai</strong></a>: Modern and elegant, located in the center of Seville (featuring a fusion of Basque, Asian, and Latin cuisines), with high-quality ingredients. Be sure to inquire about the daily specials.</li></ul><ul><li>Another one of my favorites is <a href=\\"#palo\\"><strong>Palo Cortao</strong></a>: They offer a wide variety of ?gourmet tapas,? with unbeatable quality and reasonable prices. This is the perfect place to sample Sherry, and the interior décor is elegant and contemporary.</li><li><p>If you?re looking for a more immersive experience, one option I recommend for dining today or any other day is to try <a style=\\"color: #f41b8c;\\" href=\\"#sazon\\"><b>SAZÓN The Folk Cook</b></a>, SAZON is the world\\ s first platform to provide Spanish food homely prepared by locals at their own houses, where you would taste it in complete privacy.</p></li></ul><p>In the afternoon, I suggest taking a leisurely stroll and exploring some of the gourmet shops in the city center, where you can buy (and taste) some delicacies of the city, such as:</p><ul><li><a href=\\"#sabor\\"><strong>Sabor a España</strong></a>: A unique shop that will enchant you with its aroma, which you?ll recognize from afar. It?s a traditional gourmet shop; nougat, dried fruits, marzipan, and many more that will transport you back in time.</li></ul><ul><li><a href=\\"#sierra\\"><strong>Productos de la Sierra</strong></a>: A rustic shop with high-quality regional gourmet products like wine, cheese, and olive oil.</li></ul><ul><li><a href=\\"#oleoteca\\" data-wplink-edit=\\"true\\"><strong>La Oleoteca</strong></a>: A haven for Extra Virgin Olive Oil enthusiasts. They have the best EVOOs in the world. They also offer olive oil tastings.</li></ul><p>In the late afternoon, you can head to <a href=\\"#uva\\"><strong>Lama la Uva</strong></a> wine bar to enjoy a glass of wine and the sunset next to Las Setas. The ladies who work there are wonderful. For dinner, I recommend <a href=\\"#disparate\\"><strong>El Disparate</strong></a>, a gastrobar with a pleasant and beautiful atmosphere, featuring a charming and tranquil terrace overlooking Alameda de Hércules. The service is top-notch. If not, right across, you have the <a href=\\"#aljibe\\"><strong>Al ? Aljibe</strong></a> restaurant with exquisite Mediterranean tapas. It?s located in a lovely house and has a delightful terrace upstairs.</p>                	<p>Let?s embark on a second day to leisurely enjoy Seville.</p><p> </p><p>Start with a hearty breakfast at the charming and delicious <a href=\\"#tarta\\"><strong>Tarta Home Coffee and Cake</strong></a>, right next to our experience for today.</p><p> </p><p>If yesterday we explored the Arab baths, today we?re heading to a more modern spa concept, <a href=\\"#h2o\\"><strong>H2O Spa Balneario</strong></a>. They offer various hydrothermal circuits, massages, facial and body treatments, and have a VIP room for couples.</p><p> </p><p>For lunch, now completely relaxed from the spa, you have nearby:</p><p> </p><ul><li><a href=\\"#estraperlo\\"><strong>Estraperlo</strong></a>: A fantastic experience, delicious food, and excellent service.</li></ul><ul><li><a href=\\"#fiaca\\"><strong>La Fiaca Tapas y Vinos</strong></a>: A cozy bar for enjoying tasty tapas. Their potato salad and croquettes are famous, but everything is incredible.</li></ul><p>For the afternoon, I recommend taking a leisurely stroll through Maria Luisa Park, getting lost in its gardens, lying on the grass to read a good book, heading up <a href=\\"#gurugu\\"><strong>Mount Gurugú</strong></a>, and sitting down for a coffee on the terrace of <a href=\\"#bilindo\\"><strong>Bilindo</strong></a>. Right next door, you also have the <a href=\\"#espana\\"><strong>Plaza de España</strong></a>.</p><p>To end the day, we have a very special plan. How about having dinner while sailing along the Guadalquivir? It?s spectacular. I advise you to book one of the experiences offered by Andaluza de Barcos or <a href=\\"#esturion\\"><strong>Esturión Tours</strong></a> to enjoy a private boat ride on the river with dinner included.</p>                	<p>To make the most of this morning, we recommend getting a massage at the <a href=\\"#koru\\"><strong>Koru Massage Center</strong></a>. They offer a wide range of massages, facial treatments, body treatments, and well-being experiences designed to help you relax and unwind from your daily routine.</p><p>For lunch today, we recommend:</p><ul><li><a href=\\"#cayetana\\"><strong>La Cayetana</strong></a>, a small and charming Andalusian bistro, with spectacular food. Save room for dessert; it?s worth savoring that torrija.</li></ul><ul><li><a href=\\"#brunilda\\"><strong>La Brunilda</strong></a>: a small and cozy tapas bar, pleasant atmosphere, and exquisite food.</li></ul><p>After lunch, what better way to spend the afternoon than on one of the city?s terraces, such as <strong><a style=\\"color: #f41b8c; text-decoration: underline;\\" href=\\"#puravida\\">Pura Vida</a> Terrace</strong>? Enjoy a drink or a cocktail while chatting with a view of the Giralda, savoring the sunset, and with good ambient music (sometimes they have live concerts).</p><p>An activity we can recommend for this evening is the <a href=\\"#candlelight\\"><strong>Candlelight Concerts</strong></a>, concerts illuminated by candlelight and performed by live musicians in some of the most emblematic places in Seville.</p><p>For dinner tonight, we recommend:</p><ul><li><a href=\\"#pasaje\\"><strong>El Pasaje Restaurant</strong></a>: A modern tapas bar, with a small rear patio, offering meat, fish, and seafood dishes.</li></ul><ul><li><a href=\\"#pinton\\"><strong>El Pintón</strong></a>: An excellent place to share a good meal with your partner, friends, family? exquisite food, pleasant atmosphere, and a beautiful central courtyard.</li></ul><p>After dinner, you can stroll peacefully through the illuminated streets of the city center, without hustle and bustle, admiring the beauty of every corner of <a href=\\"#constitucion\\"><strong>Constitution Avenue</strong></a>, the surroundings of the Cathedral, and the Santa Cruz District?</p><p>Enjoy and relax!</p>\t\t	367	pexels-cottonbro-studio-3997983.jpg	1100,1101,1102,1103,1104,1105,1106,1107,1108	14.9	15.65	70069.40	S	en	67,7,92,89,75,90,91,79,84,78,85,87,86,80,73,74,66,81,69,9,72,88,71,8,77,82,68	&lt;iframe src=\\"https://www.google.com/maps/d/u/2/embed?mid=14ZwnEhMAqUywpJ1rvKjlBVB5ZYhij8A&ehbc=2E312F&noprof=1\\" width=\\"640\\" height=\\"480\\"&gt;	prod_QuHtEnqyST8Y6F	price_1Q2TJmAFILSEnUZXmg5d2YeD	1	N	N	Take a break and treat yourself with your partner in Seville	\N	\N	Gourmet & Relax	prod_QuosDvxxDkmazc	price_1Q2zEzAFILSEnUZX24XVIG9a		https://buy.stripe.com/test_bIYg275x3g8u2oE7v2		plink_1Q3AniAFILSEnUZXY962DtyR	3Dias	4	N
368	S	anonimo	2024-09-23 17:09:20	2024-11-22 07:10:25	4753	2023-09-27 00:00:00	SV03 Tapas 3 days	Genuine sevillian tapas	genuine-sevillian-tapas	<strong><span style=\\"color: #ff008c;\\">Explore and Savor Sevilla\\ s Tapas Trail</span></strong>\\r\\n\\r\\nDive into the essence of Sevillian gastronomy, where tapas steal the culinary spotlight. Indulge in traditional dishes, delightful chef creations, and the warmth of the locals. This isn\\ t just about eating; it\\ s about living and embracing the tapas culture in Sevilla\\ s authentic bars	4	tapas-NEW-2.jpg	1	<p>In the Central area, you have endless possibilities. If you?re visiting the area around the Macarena Basilica, Alameda, and Plaza del Duque, you?ll find:</p><ul><li style=\\"font-weight: 400;\\" aria-level=\\"1\\">For croquette lovers, <strong><a style=\\"color: #f41b8c; text-decoration: underline;\\" href=\\"#casaricardo\\">Casa Ricardo</a></strong>. You?ll taste a delicious combination of textures with a crunchy coating and a soft, creamy interior. Always served with their shoestring potatoes.</li><li style=\\"font-weight: 400;\\" aria-level=\\"1\\"><strong><a style=\\"color: #f41b8c; text-decoration: underline;\\" href=\\"#mercadodeferia\\">Feria Street Market</a></strong>: This lively market is ideal for having beers or tapas. For example, at La Marieta, they specialize in turnovers and puff pastries (my favorite is the creamy chicken one with béchamel). La Almadraba de Barbate is great for cured fish and seafood, while La Cantina offers fried fish and shellfish. </li><li style=\\"font-weight: 400;\\" aria-level=\\"1\\">If you?re looking for a more immersive experience, one option I recommend for dining today or any other day is to try <a style=\\"color: #f41b8c;\\" href=\\"#sazon\\"><b style=\\"font-family: var(--global-body-font-family);\\">SAZÓN The Folk Cook</b></a>, SAZON is the world\\ s first platform to provide Spanish food homely prepared by locals at their own houses, where you would taste it in complete privacy.<br />Next to the market, I recommend visiting the <strong><a style=\\"color: #f41b8c; text-decoration: underline;\\" href=\\"#palaciodelosmarquesesdelaalgaba\\">Palace of the Marquises of Algaba</a></strong> (free entry and open until noon), it?s definitely worth it!</li></ul><p>In the afternoon and evening, head towards the Campana area and Plaza del Museo,</p><ul><li style=\\"font-weight: 400;\\" aria-level=\\"1\\">One of the gems of Sevillian tapas is the ?pringá? montaditos. They?re prepared with the meats used for stew, offering a mix of pork, chicken, bacon, chorizo, and blood sausage. <strong><a style=\\"color: #f41b8c; text-decoration: underline;\\" href=\\"#elpatiodesaneloy\\">El Patio de San Eloy</a></strong> started as a family business in the center of Seville and now has its own ?branch? in Triana. Be sure to try their montaditos, flamenquín, or eggplant with honey.</li><li style=\\"font-weight: 400;\\" aria-level=\\"1\\">If you prefer variety in a more sophisticated and tranquil setting, <strong><a style=\\"color: #f41b8c; text-decoration: underline;\\" href=\\"#lobolopez\\">Lobo López</a></strong> offers traditional tapas as well as fusion cuisine in a venue with artistic decorations, old arches, and columns. We recommend the curry and mango potato salad or the octopus, they?re finger-licking good! When night falls, you can have a quiet drink at <strong><a style=\\"color: #f41b8c; text-decoration: underline;\\" href=\\"#bariscariote\\">Bar Iscariote</a></strong> in Plaza del Museo, or for a livelier option in the Setas area, try <strong><a style=\\"color: #f41b8c; text-decoration: underline;\\" href=\\"#mossbar\\">Moss Bar</a></strong>.</li></ul>                	<p>Nestled in the heart of Seville, the Triana neighborhood invites you to savor an exquisite selection of local flavors and culinary traditions deeply rooted in Andalusian culture:</p><ul><li style=\\"font-weight: 400;\\" aria-level=\\"1\\"><strong><a style=\\"color: #f41b8c; text-decoration: underline;\\" href=\\"#mercadodetriana\\">Triana Market</a></strong>: It has become quite touristy in Triana, but it?s still the market where the locals shop, and they haven?t given up their space to tourists. If you go in the morning, you?ll see people buying like they?ve done all their lives. Here you have a multitude of stalls for tapas.</li><li style=\\"font-weight: 400;\\" aria-level=\\"1\\"><strong><a style=\\"color: #f41b8c; text-decoration: underline;\\" href=\\"#cervecerialagrande\\">Cervecería ?La Grande?</a></strong> for a tapa of prawns (gambas) and a beer among the locals.</li><li style=\\"font-weight: 400;\\" aria-level=\\"1\\"><strong><a style=\\"color: #f41b8c; text-decoration: underline;\\" href=\\"#barcasaruperto\\">Bar Casa Ruperto</a></strong> is one of the most authentic stops with its famous ?Pajaritos? (fried quails), snails, and ?pringá? montaditos.</li></ul><p>For an afternoon break, if you want to have a coffee or a drink, <strong><a style=\\"color: #f41b8c; text-decoration: underline;\\" href=\\"#bravo\\">Bravo</a></strong> is a very good option. In the afternoon, you must not miss visiting the chapel of the <strong><a style=\\"color: #f41b8c; text-decoration: underline;\\" href=\\"#hermandaddelaestrella\\">Brotherhood of La Estrella</a></strong> and Capilla de Los Marineros.</p><p>As evening falls in Triana? dinner time!:</p><ul><li style=\\"font-weight: 400;\\" aria-level=\\"1\\"><strong><a style=\\"color: #f41b8c; text-decoration: underline;\\" href=\\"#lasgolondrinas\\">Las Golondrinas (Antillano)</a></strong>: A charming bodega to taste their mushrooms, small squid, or tenderloin tips.</li><li style=\\"font-weight: 400;\\" aria-level=\\"1\\"><strong><a style=\\"color: #f41b8c; text-decoration: underline;\\" href=\\"#freiduriareinavictoria\\">Freiduría Reina Victoria</a></strong>: If you like fried fish in an informal atmosphere.</li></ul><p>To end the night, you can stroll through the bars on Calle Betis and have a drink at <strong><a style=\\"color: #f41b8c; text-decoration: underline;\\" href=\\"#barloladelosreyes\\">Bar Lola de los Reyes</a></strong> (if you like ?flamenquito?), or <strong><a style=\\"color: #f41b8c; text-decoration: underline;\\" href=\\"#elembarcadero\\">Embarcadero</a></strong> (by the river, closed on Sundays).</p>                	<p>We can?t forget about the famous ?carrilladas,? the quintessential tapa. In the Arenal area (near the Maestranza), you?ll find <strong><a style=\\"color: #f41b8c; text-decoration: underline;\\" href=\\"#barpepehillo\\">Bar Pepe Hillo</a></strong>, which also specializes in bull?s tail. This restaurant is one of the best places to try authentic Andalusian cuisine.</p><p>Let?s spend the afternoon in the Cathedral area and the Santa Cruz neighborhood. Here, you can have a coffee or a drink on the terrace of the <strong><a style=\\"color: #f41b8c; text-decoration: underline;\\" href=\\"#hoteldonamaria\\">Doña María Hotel</a></strong> with spectacular views. While you?re here, take a look at the lesser-known <strong><a style=\\"color: #f41b8c; text-decoration: underline;\\" href=\\"#plazadesantamarta\\">Plaza de Santa Marta</a></strong>.</p><p>You can?t leave Seville without trying the famous ?mantecaítos? at <strong><a style=\\"color: #f41b8c; text-decoration: underline;\\" href=\\"#enlaesperoteesquina\\">En la Espero te Esquina</a></strong>. A toasted ?mollete? roll, a succulent pork loin seared and slow-cooked in whisky or brandy sauce, and almost caramelized garlic, accompanied by French fries, will delight your taste buds. Another place to try ?mantecaítos? with whisky is <strong><a style=\\"color: #f41b8c; text-decoration: underline;\\" href=\\"#elfavorito\\">El Favorito</a></strong>, next to the town hall, where you can also try stuffed eggs (huevos rellenos)</p><p>If you?ve developed a taste for ?pringá,? <strong><a style=\\"color: #f41b8c; text-decoration: underline;\\" href=\\"#bodeguitaromero\\">Bodeguita Romero</a></strong> is the place to be. Their iconic corner spot and picturesque terrace whet anyone?s appetite! Here, you?ll have a good variety of tapas to choose from, including the famous ?salmorejo.?</p><p>As night falls, you can venture into the Santa Cruz neighborhood and visit <strong><a style=\\"color: #f41b8c; text-decoration: underline;\\" href=\\"#lacarboneria\\">La Carbonería</a></strong>, a tapas bar with flamenco shows in an old coal warehouse with a patio and tiled floor. There may be tourists, but it?s a must-visit spot in the Andalusian capital.</p><p>I recommend that you make restaurant reservations in advance whenever possible to ensure availability, as well as check opening hours. You can adjust the order based on your route. </p><p>I hope you enjoy it!</p>\t\t	368	tapas-NEW-2.jpg	1109,1110,1111,1112,1113,1114,1115,1116,1117	14.9	15.65	70069.40	S	en	103,99,108,110,115,104,37,102,109,114,97,113,107,24,111,16,106,55,94,20,100,96,112,8	&lt;iframe src=\\"https://www.google.com/maps/d/u/2/embed?mid=1rkRJG2fiFXTQ9hkV150NvDZ6Uf_bV-I&ehbc=2E312F&noprof=1\\" width=\\"640\\" height=\\"480\\"&gt;	prod_QuHtoAJXVcx23e	price_1Q2TJnAFILSEnUZXR110YhVE	1	N	N	Explore and Savor Sevilla\\ s Tapas Trail	\N	\N	Genuine sevillian tapas	prod_Quoslge7zMebvS	price_1Q2zEzAFILSEnUZXW8NhcCcc		https://buy.stripe.com/test_6oE5ntcZvf4q0gwbLj		plink_1Q3AniAFILSEnUZX9Zr1ML4f	3Dias	5	N
369	S	anonimo	2024-09-23 17:09:29	2024-11-22 07:10:25	4849	2023-09-28 00:00:00	SV04 Barroco 3 days	Splendor Baroque	splendor-baroque	<strong><span style=\\"color: #ff008c;\\">Following the indelible trail of Seville\\ s architectural and artistic wonders</span></strong>\\r\\n\\r\\nDiscover Seville\\ s Baroque, a blend of art, architecture, and cuisine. Explore hidden historical gems, from lesser-known majestic palaces to the Cathedral and the Royal Alcazar. Savor authentic tapas and relish nights on scenic terraces. An experience to uncover the cultural richness of churches and convents in this city.	5	Barroco-1.jpg	1	<p>Experiencing the Baroque in Seville is a journey that transports visitors to an era of artistic splendor and religious fervor. It?s like strolling through an open-air museum where every street, square, and church tells a story of grandeur and devotion. </p><p>Today, we?ll begin by visiting the <strong><a style=\\"color: #f41b8c; text-decoration: underline;\\" href=\\"#palaciodesantelmo\\">Palace of San Telmo</a></strong>, a magnificent example of Baroque architecture that has witnessed various significant events over the centuries. We?ll then head to the old <strong><a style=\\"color: #f41b8c; text-decoration: underline;\\" href=\\"#rectorado\\">Royal Tobacco Factory of Seville</a></strong>, now known as ?El Rectorado.? The building is a prominent example of Baroque architecture that has witnessed important events over the centuries. </p><p>Next, we?ll visit the <strong><a style=\\"color: #f41b8c; text-decoration: underline;\\" href=\\"#palacioarzobispal\\">Archbishop?s Palace</a></strong>, which was the residence of bishops and archbishops of episcopal sees, as well as military and nobles. </p><p>We?ll take a break for lunch. Although it has become somewhat touristy lately, it?s worth having some tapas at <strong><a style=\\"color: #f41b8c; text-decoration: underline;\\" href=\\"#bargiralda\\">Bar Giralda</a></strong>, which coexists with a 12th-century hammam and is simply spectacular.</p><p>If you?re looking for a more immersive experience, one option I recommend for dining today or any other day is to try <a style=\\"color: #f41b8c;\\" href=\\"#sazon\\"><b>SAZÓN The Folk Cook</b></a>, SAZON is the world\\ s first platform to provide Spanish food homely prepared by locals at their own houses, where you would taste it in complete privacy.</p><p>After lunch and being in this area, we certainly can?t ignore the <strong><a style=\\"color: #f41b8c; text-decoration: underline;\\" href=\\"#catedral\\">Seville Cathedral</a></strong>, one of the most impressive Baroque constructions in Spain. Its grandiose facade and majestic interior merge Baroque opulence with Gothic grandeur. And of course, La Giralda, the Cathedral?s bell tower, is an icon of the city. Its design, a fusion of Islamic, Gothic, and Renaissance styles, is a testament to the artistic transition that marked the Baroque era. </p><p>To end the afternoon, an essential visit to the <strong><a style=\\"color: #f41b8c; text-decoration: underline;\\" href=\\"#realesalcazares\\">Royal Alcazar</a></strong>, with its richly adorned halls and dreamy courtyards, is another treasure of Seville?s Baroque. Here, the fusion of architectural styles and the exuberance of decorative details create an enchanting atmosphere. </p><p>As night falls, you can treat yourselves at <strong><a style=\\"color: #f41b8c; text-decoration: underline;\\" href=\\"#fraymeliton\\">Fray Melitón</a></strong>, and have a drink at <a href=\\"#hoteleme\\"><strong>La Terraza del EME</strong></a> with spectacular views.</p>                	<p>Today, we can start the day by visiting the <a href=\\"#hospitalcaridad\\"><strong>Hospital de la Caridad</strong></a>, a prominent example of Baroque architecture. It was founded in the 17th century by the pious Sevillian Miguel de Mañara, who transformed an old chapel into a hospital to care for the sick and needy. </p><p>We?ll then head to the <a href=\\"#iglesiaelsalvador\\"><strong>Church of El Salvador</strong></a>. It?s the largest church in Seville after the Cathedral. It?s a Baroque temple that was built where the Ibn Adabbas mosque used to be, of which the prayer courtyard and the base of the minaret tower are preserved. In this area, we can stop for lunch at <a href=\\"#donaire\\"><strong>Donaire House Bar</strong></a> and recharge for the afternoon. </p><p>After lunch, we?ll venture into the Santa Cruz Neighborhood, with its cobbled streets and whitewashed courtyards, also reflecting the influence of Baroque on local architecture. Here, the wrought-iron balconies and ornate grilles are a testimony to the artistic richness of the era. Apart from wandering through its Jewish quarter streets and enjoying its orange tree courtyards, in this area, we have two mandatory stops: </p><p>The <a href=\\"#venerables\\"><strong>Hospital de los Venerables</strong></a>: with its Baroque-style church and orange tree courtyard, it?s another testament to the opulence of the era. Its decorative details, such as plasterwork and tiles, bear witness to the artistic ingenuity of the time. </p><p><strong><a style=\\"color: #f41b8c; text-decoration: underline;\\" href=\\"#santamarialablanca\\">Church of Santa María la Blanca</a></strong> (closed from Friday to Sunday): known as the ?temple of the three religions? because it was a mosque in the 10th century, a synagogue in the 12th century, and a Christian temple at the end of the 15th century after the expulsion of the Jews. It is the headquarters of the Brotherhood of the Rosary of Our Lady of the Snows, which is why it is also known as the Church of Santa María de las Nieves.</p><p>For the night, after such an eventful day, you deserve a treat at the <a href=\\"#restaurantesanfernando\\"><strong>San Fernando Restaurant</strong></a>. Another more budget-friendly option is <a href=\\"#ovejasnegras\\"><strong>Ovejas Negras</strong></a>. Afterwards, you can grab a drink at the charismatic <a href=\\"#garlochi\\"><strong>Garlochí</strong></a> (you have to try  their ?Sangre de Cristo? cocktail, is quite an experience).</p>                	<p>The sacred art of the Baroque era is also present in the numerous churches and convents of the city, where golden altars and sculpted altarpieces tell stories of faith and devotion. Today, we will visit some of them in the area of La Alameda and Las Setas:</p><p>We will begin with the <a style=\\"color: #f41b8c;\\" href=\\"#magdalena\\"><strong>Royal Parish of Santa María Magdalena</strong></a>, which boasts an impressive collection of frescoes for art and painting enthusiasts like yourselves. Additionally, you can contemplate the images of some of the most famous brotherhoods in Seville, such as La Quinta Angustia.</p><p>Next, we visit the <strong><a style=\\"color: #f41b8c; text-decoration: underline;\\" href=\\"#capillasanjose\\">Chapel of San José</a></strong>, located next to the famous Sierpes street, the shopping street of Seville.</p><p><a href=\\"#buensuceso\\"><strong>The Church of El Buen Suceso</strong></a> was built in the 17th century, although it has belonged to the Barefoot Carmelites since the 19th century. The church houses significant Baroque works by Martínez Montañés, Alonso Cano, and Pedro Roldán. It is the only vestige remaining from the Hospital of El Buen Suceso.</p><p>Today, we can have lunch at the <a href=\\"#alabardero\\"><strong>Taberna del Alabardero</strong></a> (except for Monday afternoons when it?s closed), a former palace that elevates Seville?s gastronomy with its imposing halls. If you prefer something closer, just outside the church os El Buen Suceso, you have the <a href=\\"#recoveco\\"><strong>Restaurant Recoveco</strong></a> (terrace of UNUK hotel).</p><p>There?s nothing better to start the afternoon than a visit to <a href=\\"#sanluisdelosfranceses\\"><strong>San Luis de los Franceses</strong></a>. The facade of the church is one of the most remarkable examples of Seville?s Baroque architecture. In the 20th century, the building went through a period of abandonment and deterioration. However, by the end of the century, efforts for restoration and conservation began to preserve this treasure of Seville?s heritage. Today, the Church is a cultural and artistic center that hosts cultural events, exhibitions, and concerts.</p><p>To conclude the day, we will cross over to Triana to visit the <a href=\\"#cristoexpiracion\\"><strong>Basilica del Stmo Cristo de la Expiración</strong></a>, which features a Baroque altarpiece of the Virgin of Patrocinio. Once in Triana, we can finish the day by having dinner at the <strong><a style=\\"color: #f41b8c; text-decoration: underline;\\" href=\\"#delao\\">Restaurante de la O</a></strong> or treating ourselves at <strong><a style=\\"color: #f41b8c; text-decoration: underline;\\" href=\\"#mariatrifulca\\">María Trifulca</a></strong> with its impressive views.</p><p>Enjoy!</p>\t\t	369	Barroco-1.jpg	1118,1119,1120,1121,1122,1123,1124,1125	14.9	15.65	70069.40	S	en	118,120,60,122,135,128,124,133,126,49,51,138,127,50,44,142,4,132,119,117,40,141,131,123,8,137	&lt;iframe src=\\"https://www.google.com/maps/d/u/2/embed?mid=10tN_uWCCE2XAeappm_vbGcB1Sder6W4&ehbc=2E312F&noprof=1\\" width=\\"640\\" height=\\"480\\"&gt;	prod_QuHtHAHsIXQXZR	price_1Q2TJnAFILSEnUZXV6dptqvZ	1	N	N	Following the indelible trail of Seville\\ s architectural and artistic wonders	\N	\N	Splendor Baroque	prod_QuosbsL8Kjek4g	price_1Q2zF0AFILSEnUZXw75cSUsE		https://buy.stripe.com/test_fZe3fl1gNcWibZe2aK		plink_1Q3AnjAFILSEnUZXsJT3dKnc	3Dias	6	N
375	S	anonimo	2024-09-23 17:10:39	2024-11-22 07:10:26	11392	2023-09-30 00:00:00	SV14 Game of Thrones 3 days	Game Of Thrones Fans	game-of-thrones-fans	<strong><span style=\\"color: #ff008c;\\">Discover the locations that served as the backdrop for unforgettable scenes in the famous TV series</span></strong>\\r\\n\\r\\nFollow the route that takes you through Sevilla to enjoy reminiscing about moments from the series in first person. Over three seasons, the acclaimed series has been drawn to Seville\\ s heritage to film, showcasing the city\\ s epic and glorious face <strong>(car required for some days)</strong>	11	gotsevilla.jpg	1	<p>At the <a href=\\"#alcazar\\"><strong>Royal Alcazar of Seville</strong></a> (book your tickets in advance on the website https://www.realalcazarsevilla.com/), the Water Gardens were represented, the palatial residence of the Martells in the capital of Dorne. Specifically, in the Garden of the Ladies and the Gallery of the Grotesque, the scene stands out from a loggia over the Mercury Pond, where Ellaria Sand, alongside Doran Martell, watches as Myrcella Lannister strolls through the Garden of the Ladies with her betrothed, Trystane Martell. You will see the impressive rooms, many decorated with Mudéjar-style mosaics, which were used as the interiors of the Water Gardens.</p><p>In the sumptuous Ambassadors? Hall, the scene was filmed in which Jaime Lannister met with the Martells to negotiate Myrcella Lannister?s return to King?s Landing. It?s interesting because they didn?t need to add any computer-generated imagery, only the introduction of some curtains and furniture was enough, perfectly simulating the House of Martell. The Baths of Maria de Padilla is the place where Ellaria Sand incited the Sand Snakes to rebel.</p><p>Since you?re in the area, take the opportunity to visit the lesser-known <a href=\\"#cabildo\\"><strong>Cabildo Square</strong></a> near the cathedral. Very close to the square, you?ll find another iconic setting from GOT: </p><p>The <a href=\\"#atarazanas\\"><strong>Royal Shipyards of Seville</strong></a> (Atarazanas de Sevilla): Unfortunately, at this moment, they are closed to the public (they are under renovation, and the expectation is that they will be open to the public sometime in 2023 or January 2024). It is an ancient medieval shipyard, the best-preserved in the world, where the basements beneath the Red Keep of King?s Landing are recreated. Qyburn, Cersei, and Jaime play decisive scenes in this location, desperately trying to escape the Red Keep through the dungeons. In one scene, the former maester reassures Queen Lannister by showing her a powerful weapon, a giant crossbow, which is stored in a kind of underground catacomb or warehouse. In that space, there are also several dragon skeletons, perhaps left as a reminder. The scene is dark, and only the torches hanging on the walls illuminate it, but the arches and vaults of the shipyards are perfectly recognizable. :)</p><p>Since you?re in the city center, you can enjoy tapas at <a href=\\"#ovejas\\"><strong>Ovejas Negras</strong></a>, a fusion of Asian and Spanish tapas, or visit the restaurant <a href=\\"#circo\\"><strong>Pan y Circo</strong></a>, a very original restaurant-gallery of art. If you?re looking for a more immersive experience, one option I recommend for dining today or any other day is to try <a style=\\"color: #f41b8c;\\" href=\\"#sazon\\"><b style=\\"font-family: var(--global-body-font-family);\\">SAZÓN The Folk Cook</b></a>, SAZON is the world\\ s first platform to provide Spanish food homely prepared by locals at their own houses, where you would taste it in complete privacy.</p><p><br />Next to the market, I recommend visiting the <strong><a style=\\"color: #f41b8c; text-decoration: underline;\\" href=\\"#algaba\\">Palace of the Marquises of Algaba</a></strong> (free entry and open until noon), it?s definitely worth it!</p><p>In the afternoon, take the opportunity to visit the <a href=\\"#caridad\\"><strong>Hospital de la Caridad</strong></a>, and of course, wander through the Santa Cruz neighborhood. You can get lost in its narrow streets of the Jewish quarter and orange tree patios (one example is the <a href=\\"#elvira\\"><strong>Doña Elvira Square</strong></a>), and its streets were the setting for the movie ?Nobody Knows Anybody? with Eduardo Noriega.</p><p>As night falls, you can have some tapas at <a href=\\"#columnas\\"><strong>Bar Santa Cruz ?Las Columnas? </strong></a>(Bodega ?Santa Cruz?) with an extensive menu of tapas, or treat yourself at the <a href=\\"#marco\\"><strong>San Marcos Santa Cruz restaurant</strong></a> (Italian cuisine), located in a 12th-century Arab bathhouse.</p><p>Since you?re in the area, you can have a drink at the charismatic <a href=\\"#garlochi\\"><strong>Garlochí</strong></a> and try their ?Sangre de Cristo? cocktail (blood of Christ). </p>                	<p>In the morning, we can visit the impressive <a style=\\"color: #f41b8c; text-decoration: underline;\\" href=\\"#espana\\"><b>Plaza de España</b></a>, which has been a backdrop for great movies like Star Wars, The Dictator, or Lawrence of Arabia. Take a walk in <a href=\\"#luisa\\"><b>María Luisa Park</b></a> and visit the <a href=\\"#arts\\"><b>Museum of Popular Arts ans Traditions</b></a>.</p><p>For lunch in the area you have <a href=\\"#estraperlo\\"><b>Estraperlo </b></a>(closed on mondays).</p><p>After lunch, we can explore the area around Alameda de Hércules and can visit the <a href=\\"#luis\\"><b>Monumental ensemble of Saint Louis of the French</b></a> (closes at 5 pm), and the <a href=\\"#pilatos\\"><b>Casa Pilatos</b></a> (open from 10 am to 8 pm), and the which is sure to captivate you, a beautiful place with a lot of history.</p><p>In the evening, <a href=\\"#alameda\\"><b>alameda de Hércules</b></a> has a bohemian and lively atmosphere in its countless terraces! In this area, I recommend some tapas in the funny <a href=\\"#lola\\"><b>Lola por Dios</b></a>, or if you like Mexican food, the restaurant <a href=\\"#santo\\"><b>Mano de Santo</b></a>. To end the night, enjoy a beer or a drink in one of its terraces like the one at <a href=\\"#central\\"><b>Café Central</b></a>.</p>                	<p>Today we?re going to leave Seville. We will visit the <a href=\\"#italica\\"><b>Ruins of Italica</b></a>, which served as Pozo Dragón in the seventh and eighth seasons. This dragon?s lair is the setting for some of the most epic scenes in the series. Since you?re in Santiponce, don?t forget to visit the <a style=\\"color: #f41b8c;\\" href=\\"#isidoro\\"><b>Monastery of San Isidoro del Campo</b></a> (except if you go on Monday when it?s closed). For lunch in the area, I recommend <a href=\\"#canario\\"><b>Ventorrillo</b><b> Cana</b><b>rio</b></a>, specializing in grilled meats.</p><p>Another filming location for the series was in Osuna, a wonderful city full of art, culture, and worthy corners to explore. You can take a stroll through the town and visit the well-known <strong><a style=\\"color: #f41b8c; text-decoration: underline;\\" href=\\"#colegiata\\" target=\\"_blank\\" rel=\\"noopener\\">Collegiate Church of Our Lady of the Assumption</a></strong> (opens until 2:30 PM, closed on Mondays). If you haven?t eaten yet, in Osuna we recommend <a href=\\"#curro\\"><b>Casa Curro</b></a>, which once named some of its dishes in honor of the series!</p><p>After lunch, we can visit the <a href=\\"#osuna\\"><b>old bullring</b></a> that was used as a set in the fifth season, transformed into the Daznak?s Pit in Meereen and the place where many bloody battles were filmed. The bullring only opens on Saturdays and Sundays from 16 to 18. </p><p>To bid farewell, we can spend the end of the day in the Triana neighborhood, before you can stroll along the <a href=\\"#contadero\\"><b>Paseo del Marqués del Contadero</b></a> and cross the <a href=\\"#triana\\"><b>Triana bridge</b></a>, just like in the famous spanish movie ?8 Apellidos Vascos.?</p><p>If the night falls while you?re in Triana, you can have dinner at <a href=\\"#paco\\"><b>Taberna Paco España</b></a>, or if you want to treat yourselves, <a href=\\"#21\\"><b>Alfarería 21</b></a>. Later, you can have a drink on the terrace of <a href=\\"#bribon\\"><b>Bribón </b></a>with views of the bridge, or stay in calle betis that is full of flamenco bars like <a href=\\"#martinez\\"><b>Los Martinez Premium</b></a>, Lo nuestro, Lola de los reyes?If you want to see a flamenco show in the area, I like the one at <a href=\\"#tablao\\"><strong>Teatro Flamenco Triana</strong></a>.</p><p>I recommend booking restaurants and events in advance to ensure availability, as well as checking opening hours.</p><p>I hope you enjoy this weekend in Seville, and we hope to see you back soon? Dracarys!</p>\t\t	375	gotsevilla.jpg	1163,1164,1165,1166,1130,1167,1168,1169,1170,1171,1172	14.9	15.65	70069.40	S	en	2,227,329,280,263,39,260,328,266,79,133,126,199,28,323,168,4,169,132,96,236,331,10,9,330,53,305,123,264,265,147,8,333,22,332	&lt;iframe src=\\"https://www.google.com/maps/d/u/2/embed?mid=1F78B1R2Loj07IFN5pY0ASWSbcvoXYzo&ehbc=2E312F&noprof=1\\" width=\\"640\\" height=\\"480\\"&gt;	prod_QuHtOupr0Qq4Fs	price_1Q2TJqAFILSEnUZXBEflfRnn	1	N	N	Discover the locations that served as the backdrop for unforgettable scenes in the famous TV series	\N	\N	Game Of Thrones Fans	prod_Quos9cHAPruE76	price_1Q2zF3AFILSEnUZX7b2ABJZR		https://buy.stripe.com/test_5kA3flcZve0m5AQaHj		plink_1Q3AnmAFILSEnUZXgW8qtX4x	3Dias	12	N
370	S	anonimo	2024-09-23 17:09:43	2024-11-22 00:14:05	4882	2023-09-28 00:00:00	SV07 Imprescindibles 3 days	Must-Visit Spots and Tasty Delights	must-visit-spots-and-tasty-delights	<div><span style=\\"color: #ff008c;\\"><strong>An Unforgettable Tour of Seville\\ s Iconic Places and Authentic Flavors</strong></span></div>\\r\\n<div>Get ready for an exciting adventure on your first visit to Seville, the capital of Andalusia. Explore the city\\ s most iconic spots and savor the delicious local cuisine at the restaurants beloved by locals. Immerse yourself in its history and culture, and dive into the passion of live flamenco performances. Sevilla is ready to offer you an unforgettable experience filled with fascinating places and genuine flavors.</div>	6	la-giralda-sevilla.jpg	1	<p>What better way to begin your visit to the capital of Andalusia than at the <a style=\\"color: #f41b8c;\\" href=\\"#alcazar\\"><strong>Alcázar of Seville</strong></a>? Here, we?ll spend the morning admiring this beautiful Royal Palace and its dreamlike gardens.</p><p>Upon leaving, head to the Santa Cruz neighborhood (use the Plaza del <a href=\\"#patiodebanderas\\"><strong>Patio de Banderas</strong></a> as a reference to capture the famous photo under the arch leading to the fountain on <a href=\\"#fuentejuderia\\"><strong>Calle de la Judería</strong></a> with the Giralda in the background). If you get hungry, you can grab a bite at <a href=\\"#lascolumnas\\"><strong>Bar Santa Cruz ?Las Columnas?</strong></a> or at the Italian restaurant <a href=\\"#sanmarcosantacruz\\"><strong>San Marco Santa Cruz</strong></a> located in some Arabic baths.</p><p>If you?re looking for a more immersive experience, one option I recommend for dining today or any other day is to try <a style=\\"color: #f41b8c;\\" href=\\"#sazon\\"><b>SAZÓN The Folk Cook</b></a>, SAZON is the world\\ s first platform to provide Spanish food homely prepared by locals at their own houses, where you would taste it in complete privacy.</p><p>In the afternoon, we?ll head towards the <a href=\\"#catedral\\"><strong>Cathedral</strong></a>. If you?d like, you can climb the Giralda and marvel at the panoramic views of Seville (from Monday to Friday, between 14:00 and 15:00, the visit is free until capacity is reached). If you fancy a coffee with spectacular views, I have a clear recommendation?the terrace of the <a style=\\"color: #f41b8c;\\" href=\\"#donamaria\\"><strong>Doña María Hotel</strong></a>. After the Giralda, you can visit the <a href=\\"#archivodeindias\\"><strong>General Archive of the Indies</strong></a> and the lesser-known <a href=\\"#cabildo\\"><strong>Plaza del Cabildo</strong></a>. Then, continue towards <a style=\\"color: #f41b8c;\\" href=\\"#setas\\"><strong>Las Setas</strong></a> and the <a href=\\"#duenas\\"><strong>Palacio de Dueñas</strong></a>. Nearby, you can have a drink at <a href=\\"#elrinconcillo\\"><strong>El Rinconcillo</strong></a>, or if you prefer something more sophisticated, head to the terrace of <a href=\\"#unuk\\"><strong>Unuk Hotel</strong></a> and its restaurant Recoveco. To end the day, you can stay for a drink on the terrace or visit the charismatic <a href=\\"#garlochi\\"><strong>Garlochí</strong></a>.</p>                	<p>Today, we?re heading to the birthplace of flamenco: the neighborhood of Triana. You can have breakfast at <a href=\\"#labaronesa\\"><strong>La Baronesa</strong></a> and then visit the famous <a style=\\"color: #f41b8c;\\" href=\\"#mercadodetriana\\"><strong>Triana market</strong></a> and the <a href=\\"#castillosanjorge\\"><strong>San Jorge Castle</strong></a>.</p><p>Stroll along Calle Betis along the Guadalquivir River and wander until you find the charming <a href=\\"#plazuela\\"><strong>Santa Ana Square</strong></a>. Of course, in this area, you must visit the famous <a href=\\"#marineros\\"><strong>Capilla de los Marineros</strong></a> on Calle Pureza and take a walk down San Jacinto (the main pedestrian street in Triana, apart from Calle Betis). For lunch, you can stay at <a href=\\"#barbistec\\"><strong>Bar Bistec</strong></a> in the same square, or go to <a href=\\"#golondrinas\\"><strong>Las Golondrinas</strong></a> on Pagés del Corro Street.</p><p>After lunch, cross the impressive <a href=\\"#puentedetriana\\"><strong>Isabel II Bridge</strong></a> and explore the other side of the river along Paseo Cristóbal Colón to reach the <a href=\\"#torredeloro\\"><strong>Torre del Oro</strong></a>, which has witnessed historical moments like Magellan and Elcano?s expedition. If you?re up for it, you can go inside and visit. Then, continue on to the <a href=\\"#rectorado\\"><strong>Royal Tobacco Factory of Seville</strong></a>, which is now the University of Seville.</p><p>Seville doesn?t end there! Next, we?ll visit the <a href=\\"#marialuisa\\"><strong>María Luisa Park</strong></a>, where you must take photos at Plaza de España and Plaza de América. It?s quite fascinating to explore the <a href=\\"#artesycostumbres\\"><strong>Museum of Arts and Popular Customs of Seville</strong></a> here. Before heading home, you can enjoy tapas at <a href=\\"#ovejas\\"><strong>Ovejas Negras</strong></a> or treat yourself at <a href=\\"#ozama\\"><strong>Casa Ozama</strong></a> if you?re looking for something more chic. In the evening, you can have a drink at <a href=\\"#lacarboneria\\"><strong>La Carbonería</strong></a>, where you?ll find flamenco shows and a variety of entertainment.</p>                	<p>Seville is endless! Today we?ll explore the Macarena area, <a style=\\"color: #f41b8c;\\" href=\\"#sanluis\\"><strong>San Luis de los Franceses</strong></a>, and the <a href=\\"#algaba\\"><strong>Palace of the Marquises of Algaba</strong></a>. For lunch, make a stop at the <a href=\\"#mercadodeferia\\"><strong>Feria Market</strong></a> and enjoy fried fish, tapas, and a variety of dishes from any of its stalls.</p><p>After lunch, we?ll visit the <a href=\\"#macarena\\"><strong>Basilica of La Macarena</strong></a> and its brotherhood museum, then continue on to the <a href=\\"#granpoder\\"><strong>Basilica of Jesus of the Gran Poder</strong></a>. We?ll finish by strolling through <a href=\\"#alameda\\"><strong>Alameda de Hércules</strong></a>, which is brimming with terraces offering a unique and bohemian atmosphere. You have plenty of options to grab a drink, such as <a href=\\"#veneranda\\"><strong>Veneranda Café</strong></a> or the terrace of the <a href=\\"#patioalameda\\"><strong>Patio de la Alameda Hotel</strong></a>. For dinner, I recommend <a href=\\"#guadalquivir\\"><strong>Casa Manolo León (Guadalquivir)</strong></a>. Another option, if you enjoy flamenco shows in a completely Sevillian setting, is right next to La Macarena?the <a href=\\"#torresmacarena\\"><strong>Torres Macarena Flamenco Cultural Center</strong></a>, which offers flamenco shows almost daily and has a terrace for dining or having a drink (please check opening hours).</p><p>We recommend making restaurant and event reservations in advance to ensure availability, as well as checking opening hours.</p><p>Enjoy your time and come back soon to discover more of this city that, as the song says, has a special color :)</p>\t\t	370	la-giralda-sevilla.jpg	1126,1127,1128,1129,1130,1131,1132,1133,1134	14.9	15.65	70069.40	S	en	2,151,25,157,1,23,182,170,160,122,46,144,111,180,138,34,59,16,54,21,153,168,94,20,4,169,132,154,96,145,6,53,161,18,123,167,147,8,166,179	&lt;iframe src=\\"https://www.google.com/maps/d/u/2/embed?mid=1NhAWiOr8QNhhEbrYiuWOwY6k5lXRCOE&ehbc=2E312F&noprof=1\\" width=\\"640\\" height=\\"480\\"&gt;	prod_QuHt5SN5Cuysa9	price_1Q2TJoAFILSEnUZXgPqPNSMD	1	N	N	An Unforgettable Tour of Seville\\ s Iconic Places and Authentic Flavors	\N	\N	Must-Visit Spots and Tasty Delights	prod_Qv1GVKSGldNKgS	price_1Q3BEQAFILSEnUZXyU3ilbpn		https://buy.stripe.com/test_5kAeY3gbH9K66EUcRE		plink_1Q3BIZAFILSEnUZXgiwvtGlN	3Dias	7	N
371	S	anonimo	2024-09-23 17:09:55	2024-11-22 07:10:25	4926	2023-09-29 00:00:00	SV09 Budget 3 days	Seville on a Budget	seville-on-a-budget	<div><strong><span style=\\"color: #ff008c;\\">Explore the City Authentically on a Budget</span></strong></div>\\r\\n<div></div>\\r\\n<div>Discover Sevilla without breaking the bank. Dive into its charming neighborhoods, squares, museums, and iconic spots. Don\\ t miss our recommendations for savoring authentic local cuisine at wallet-friendly prices. Immerse yourself in the rich Sevillian culture with this experience.</div>	7	Mercado-el-Postigo.jpg	1	<p>We?ll start in the bustling area of Avenida de la Constitución. For breakfast, you can head to <a href=\\"#ninos\\"><strong>Bar Los Niños</strong></a>, where you can enjoy a very affordable breakfast. Afterwards, take a look at <a href=\\"#postigo\\"><strong>El Postigo Market</strong></a> and continue our route by visiting the beautiful <a href=\\"#cabildo\\"><strong>Plaza del Cabildo</strong></a>, a hidden gem right in the heart of Seville.</p><p> </p><p>Afterwards, you can visit the <a href=\\"#archivo\\"><strong>Archivo de Indias</strong></a>, which has free entry. This archive is a treasure trove of documents that narrate the golden age of exploration and colonization of America. Founded in 1785, it houses an impressive collection of historical documents, including maps, letters, and administrative records, which bear witness to the cultural richness and legacy of the Spanish colonial period.</p><p> </p><p>If you want to visit the <a href=\\"#catedral\\"><strong>Cathedral</strong></a> and the Giralda, free visits take place from Monday to Friday (except holidays) with an entry time from 2:00 pm to 3:00 pm. Due to organization reasons, the daily capacity is limited, and the acquisition of this type of ticket can only be done through the monument?s website </p><p> </p><p>For lunch, we?ll stop at <a href=\\"#chari\\"><strong>Bar Kiko de la Chari</strong></a>, offering very cheap daily menus and combined dishes?a literal taste of grandma?s homemade cooking. If you fancy hamburgers, <a href=\\"#toby\\"><strong>Toby Eats the World</strong></a> is an option with a terrace and views of the Torre del Oro, offering burger menus at 16.50 euros and salad menus at 17.50 euros.</p><p> </p><p>If you come to this area on a Monday, you can also visit the <a href=\\"#alcazar\\"><strong>Alcázar of Seville</strong></a> for free: On Mondays from October to March from 4:00 pm to 5:00 pm, and from April to September from 6:00 pm to 7:00 pm, you don?t have to pay anything. Reservations usually fill up well in advance and can be made through the website </p><p> </p><p>In the afternoon, we?ll explore the Santa Cruz neighborhood. Get lost in its cobbled streets and orange tree courtyards, like the one in <a href=\\"#elvira\\"><strong>Plaza de Doña Elvira</strong></a>. Don?t forget to visit the Fountain on Calle Judería and then head to <a href=\\"#banderas\\"><strong>Patio de Banderas</strong></a>, where you can take a great photo with the arch and the Giralda in the background. Don?t miss a walk through <a href=\\"#murillo\\"><strong>the gardens of Murillo</strong></a>.</p><p> </p><p>At night, you can enjoy tapas at <a href=\\"#columnas\\"><strong>Bar Santa Cruz ?Las Columnas?</strong></a> with a wide menu at affordable prices. Then, take a stroll through Plaza Nueva and Avenida de la Constitución, where cultural events and street performances often take place.</p>                	<p>Today we will start the morning by visiting the well-known <a href=\\"#macarena\\"><strong>Basilica of La Macarena</strong></a>, an emblem of devotion and religious heritage. Built in the 20th century, this majestic basilica is home to the Virgin of Hope of Macarena, one of the most venerated images of Seville?s Holy Week. Next, we?ll visit the <a href=\\"#sanluis\\"><strong>Church of San Luis de los Franceses</strong></a> (entrance is 4 euros, and on Sunday afternoons, it?s free), a lesser-known architectural gem. After that, we?ll continue to the <a href=\\"#algaba\\"><strong>Palace of the Marquises of Algaba</strong></a> (it?s free and closes at 2 pm). Don?t forget to visit <a href=\\"#mercadodeferia\\"><strong>Feria Market</strong></a> on your way out and enjoy a beer or whatever you prefer.</p><p>For lunch, we can head to Alameda and have tapas at the fun <a href=\\"#lolapordios\\"><strong>Lola por Dios</strong></a>. Or, if it?s Monday to Thursday, you can try La <a href=\\"#calle\\"><strong>Calle Burger</strong></a> (Set menu for two people 23.95: 1 starter, 2 main burgers or sandwiches, and 2 drinks).</p><p>In the afternoon, we?ll head out to explore Triana, crossing the bridge with stunning views of the Guadalquivir River. To spend the afternoon, we can have ice cream at <a href=\\"#limones\\"><strong>María Limones</strong></a> (my favorite is the pistachio flavor), and then visit the chapels of the <a href=\\"#estrella\\"><strong>Brotherhood of La Estrella</strong></a> and <a href=\\"#marineros\\"><strong>Los Marineros</strong></a>, and watch the sunset around the bridge.</p><p>For dinner, a good, lovely, and budget-friendly option is <a href=\\"#bartriana\\"><strong>Bar Triana</strong></a>. Another choice is the <a href=\\"#saneloy\\"><strong>Patio de San Eloy (Triana)</strong></a>. After dinner, you can stroll along Calle Betis and have a drink at one of its flamenco bars, for example, at <a href=\\"#lola\\"><strong>Lola de los Reyes</strong></a>.</p>                	<p>Today we can visit the <a href=\\"#artesycostumbres\\"><strong>Museum of Arts and Popular Customs of Seville</strong></a>, which is free for EU citizens, and for those who aren?t, it only costs 1.50 euros. Since we?re in the area, we can?t miss the Maria Luisa Park and its gardens, and the essential <a href=\\"#espana\\"><strong>Plaza de España</strong></a>. In this square, there are often street flamenco performances under some of its arches. I hope you?re lucky enough to catch one!</p><p>Afterwards, we can return to the city center for lunch at <a href=\\"#caserio\\"><strong>Er Caserío</strong></a>. You can try one of their famous tapas, like the stuffed tuna eggs (huevos rellenos) with a generous dollop of mayonnaise on top? absolutely delicious!</p><p>In the afternoon, we?ll visit the <a href=\\"#bellasartes\\"><strong>Museum of Fine Arts</strong></a>, which is also free for EU citizens (1.50 euros for those outside the EU), and we?ll take the opportunity to visit some of Seville?s most well-known churches, such as the <a href=\\"#magdalena\\"><strong>Royal Parish of Santa María Magdalena de Sevilla</strong></a>, the <a href=\\"#catalina\\"><strong>Church of Santa Catalina</strong></a>, or the <a href=\\"#suceso\\"><strong>Church of El Buen Suceso</strong></a>.</p><p>For dinner, I?ll give you two options: <a href=\\"#claveles\\"><strong>Los Claveles</strong></a>, or if you?d like to experience a flamenco show at affordable prices, you can visit the <a href=\\"#torresmacarena\\"><strong>Torres Macarena Flamenco Club</strong></a>, an intimate flamenco venue with a live show in its courtyard where they serve tapas and chilled beer, along with a charming terrace in a very Sevillian atmosphere.</p><p>To end the night in a bohemian and lively atmosphere, you can have a drink on the terraces of Alameda, for example, at <a href=\\"#central\\"><strong>Café Central</strong></a>.</p><p>I recommend making reservations in advance for restaurants and events to ensure availability, as well as checking schedules.</p><p>Enjoy!</p>\t\t	371	Mercado-el-Postigo.jpg	1135,1136,1299,1138,1139,1140	14.9	15.65	70069.40	S	en	151,188,183,204,1,39,23,122,209,24,43,44,193,200,54,206,199,45,201,94,184,4,210,169,96,40,145,205,6,10,9,53,123,189	&lt;iframe src=\\"https://www.google.com/maps/d/u/2/embed?mid=1F5x2DY7ASrjODxKG7-ZsDQSrsqkMKIo&ehbc=2E312F&noprof=1\\" width=\\"640\\" height=\\"480\\"&gt;	prod_QuHtckP45OeEoS	price_1Q2TJoAFILSEnUZXQrRJfDnf	1	N	N	Explore the City Authentically on a Budget	\N	\N	Seville on a Budget	prod_Quosvtf54CZ0la	price_1Q2zF1AFILSEnUZXgfWYjaa2		https://buy.stripe.com/test_dR6bLR8Jff4qd3ibLl		plink_1Q3AnkAFILSEnUZX1cWEyLYe	3Dias	8	N
372	S	anonimo	2024-09-23 17:10:04	2024-11-22 07:10:26	4985	2023-09-29 00:00:00	SV10 Cosmopolita&Urban 3 days	Cosmopolita&Urban	cosmopolitaurban	<strong><span style=\\"color: #ff008c;\\">Discover the Cosmopolitan Side of Sevilla</span></strong>\\r\\n\\r\\n<span style=\\"font-weight: 400;\\">Uncover hidden palaces and savor exquisite brunches while immersing yourself in the city\\ s cultural richness. You won\\ t miss out on trendy spots and the most elegant corners of the Híspalis capital, offering you a unique experience full of style and sophistication. Explore a Sevilla that will steal your heart!</span>\\r\\n\\r\\n&nbsp;	8	Maquiavelo.jpg	1	<p>To start off on the right foot, there?s nothing better than a visit to the <a style=\\"color: #f41b8c;\\" href=\\"#alcazar\\"><strong>Royal Alcazars</strong></a>, an architectural gem of the city. They are a treasure trove of history and culture. This imposing fortress and royal palace have witnessed centuries of reigns and transformations. Its exquisite architecture combines Islamic, Mudejar, Gothic, Renaissance, and Baroque elements, creating a fascinating mosaic of styles.</p><p>After this visit, we can have lunch on the terrace of the <a style=\\"color: #f41b8c;\\" href=\\"#hotelpalacio\\"><strong>Palacio Alcázar Hotel</strong></a>, where you can enjoy fantastic views of the cathedral. You can finish the meal with a good coffee or start it with a glass of wine. If you prefer something more casual and authentic, you can have some tapas at <a href=\\"#ovejas\\"><strong>Ovejas Negras</strong></a>, very close to the Cathedral.</p><p>You can use the afternoon to stroll through the Santa Cruz neighborhood, with its narrow cobbled streets and flower-filled courtyards, it?s a maze of charm and mystery. Here, whitewashed walls and wrought-iron balconies create an atmosphere that evokes the soul of old Seville. Since we?re in Seville, we should experience a flamenco show. In this area, I really like <a href=\\"#casaflamenco\\"><strong>La Casa del Flamenco</strong></a> with a very complete show and several performances every evening.</p><p>To end the day, a delicious dinner at <a href=\\"#maquiavelo\\"><strong>Maquiavelo</strong></a> Restaurant (closed on Mondays), a must-visit in the Andalusian capital. You can stay afterwards for a drink. Another option would be <a href=\\"#casacarmen\\"><strong>Casa Carmen Restaurant</strong></a>, which also has a spectacular terrace with views of Torre de la Plata, perfect for a post-dinner drink.</p><p>If you?re looking for a more immersive experience, one option I recommend for dining today or any other day is to try <a style=\\"color: #f41b8c;\\" href=\\"#sazon\\"><b>SAZÓN The Folk Cook</b></a>, SAZON is the world\\ s first platform to provide Spanish food homely prepared by locals at their own houses, where you would taste it in complete privacy.</p>                	<p>Today, we?ll visit the Triana neighborhood. You can start the day right at <a href=\\"#bravo\\"><strong>Bravo</strong></a> with a great variety of breakfast options right on Calle San Jacinto.</p><p>In Triana, there?s so much to see. You can?t leave without visiting the <a href=\\"#marineros\\"><strong>Capilla de los Marineros</strong></a> with the highly venerated image of the Esperanza de Triana, as well as the famous <a href=\\"#mercado\\"><strong>Triana Market</strong></a>. Take the opportunity to stop at any of the stalls to try paella, fried fish, or iberian ham.  If you?re looking for an option outside the market: <a href=\\"#alfareria21\\"><strong>Alfarería 21</strong></a>.</p><p>After lunch, we can take a cruise on the Guadalquivir River. <a href=\\"#esturion\\"><strong>Esturión Tours</strong></a> has two boarding points, one at the San Telmo Bridge and another just below the <a href=\\"#sanjorge\\"><strong>San Jorge Castle</strong></a>. I?ll provide the booking information in the points of interest below.</p><p>For dinner, I have a clear choice: <a href=\\"#mariatrifulca\\"><strong>Mariatrifulca</strong></a>, with spectacular views of the river and the Triana Bridge. And if you want to have a drink later, head to <a href=\\"#elembarcadero\\"><strong>El Embarcadero</strong></a>. Along the way, you?ll find a good variety of flamenco bars on Calle Betis. Next to it, you have another option for dinner, <a href=\\"#riogrande\\"><strong>Rio Grande</strong></a>, also by the river.</p>                	<p>Today, we?ll focus on some cultural visits. To fuel up in the area we?ll be visiting, I recommend <a href=\\"#cacharreria\\"><strong>La Cacharrería</strong></a>, with great breakfast options, cakes, and even the possibility of brunch.</p><p>With our stomachs full, we head to the <a href=\\"#lebrija\\"><strong>Palace of the Countess of Lebrija</strong></a>. Although it?s unknown to many, the building is spectacular. In the 16th century, the nobility of Lebrija acquired the property and carried out significant renovations in the Renaissance style, while preserving original elements from the Roman era, such as mosaics and columns. Sculptures, tapestries, or furniture of high historical-artistic value. The list of artworks that ?inhabit? the <a href=\\"#duenas\\"><strong>Palace of Dueñas</strong></a> seems endless. Neri di Bicci, Mariano Benlliure, or Luca Giordano are just some of the authors of the many pieces housed in the Sevillian residence of the Duke of Alba, Carlos Fitz-James Stuart.</p><p>For lunch in this area, you have <a style=\\"color: #f41b8c;\\" href=\\"#panycirco\\"><strong>Pan y Circo</strong></a>, which has an art gallery you can visit, or the <a href=\\"#alabardero\\"><strong>Taberna del Alabardero Restaurant</strong></a>, located in an old mansion on Zaragoza Street.</p><p>To spend the afternoon, there?s nothing better than getting to know the latest great project of contemporary Andalusian architecture, the Metrosol Parasol, better known as the <a href=\\"#setas\\"><strong>Setas of Seville</strong></a>. It?s a wooden structure designed by the Berlin architect Jünger Mayer. There are six colossal parasols, inspired by the vaults of the cathedral, which shelter the Antiquarium Museum underground; an immense town square above, and crowning the Mushrooms, an immense viewpoint with spectacular views of the city and its surroundings, and the unique gastronomic space, GastroSol.</p><p>To say goodbye, have dinner at <a href=\\"#guadalquivir\\"><strong>Casa Manolo León (Guadalquivir)</strong></a>, or if you want to stay close to the Mushrooms, try the <strong><a style=\\"color: #f41b8c; text-decoration: underline;\\" href=\\"#unuk\\">Recoveco Restaurant</a></strong> and its terrace at the Unuk Hotel, specializing in almadraba tuna. You can stay for a drink afterward or head to one of the terraces near the Mushrooms, like the one at <a href=\\"#moss\\"><strong>Moss Bar</strong></a>.</p><p>We recommend booking restaurants and events in advance to ensure availability, as well as checking opening hours.</p><p>Enjoy!</p>\t\t	372	Maquiavelo.jpg	1141,1142,1143,1144,1145,1146	14.9	15.65	70069.40	S	en	227,104,23,222,182,160,109,84,218,138,233,14,153,221,142,20,100,132,234,154,236,232,123,8,137	&lt;iframe src=\\"https://www.google.com/maps/d/u/2/embed?mid=1EFoVIEQ-I3tle3L3KKSD9VjsV9pWwys&ehbc=2E312F&noprof=1\\" width=\\"640\\" height=\\"480\\"&gt;	prod_QuHtbiA9zrDxi8	price_1Q2TJpAFILSEnUZX85VQbSEl	1	N	N	Discover the Cosmopolitan Side of Sevilla	\N	\N	Cosmopolita&Urban	prod_Qv1GqyxA6MJWtk	price_1Q3BERAFILSEnUZXWODUjlkF		https://buy.stripe.com/test_dR65nt1gN1dAfbqaJx		plink_1Q3BIaAFILSEnUZXzwoosT6E	3Dias	9	N
373	S	anonimo	2024-09-23 17:10:15	2024-11-22 07:10:26	5062	2023-09-30 00:00:00	SV11 Movie 3 days	Movie Sets	movie-sets	<strong><span style=\\"color: #ff008c;\\">Discover Seville as if you were in a movie</span></strong>\\r\\n\\r\\n<span style=\\"font-weight: 400;\\">Explore Seville through this exciting route that will take you to the movie settings of the city. From the charm of Triana to the grandeur of Plaza de España, you can experience the scenes from your favorite movies. We also have some recommendations for you to enjoy the vibrant nightlife in Seville.</span>	9	pexels-sami-abdullah-7359476.jpg	1	<p>On the first day, if you arrive early, you can take a stroll through the picturesque neighborhood of Triana, where films like the spanish ?Your Son? were shot. Triana is like a canvas where tradition, history, and Andalusian culture intertwine. Its cobbled, narrow streets open up to welcoming squares and vibrant, colorful courtyards. Don?t forget to visit the <a href=\\"#ana\\"><strong>parish of Santa Ana</strong></a>, a living history of Triana, and, of course, explore the market with countless stalls of all kinds. In this area, you can have a beer and some gambas at <a href=\\"#grande\\"><strong>Cervecería la Grande</strong></a>, or enjoy tapas at <a href=\\"#golondrinas\\"><strong>Las Golondrinas</strong></a> on Pagés del Corro Street. If you?re looking for a more immersive experience, one option I recommend for dining today or any other day is to try <a style=\\"color: #f41b8c; text-decoration: underline;\\" href=\\"#sazon\\"><b style=\\"font-family: var(--global-body-font-family);\\">SAZÓN The Folk Cook</b></a>, SAZON is the world\\ s first platform to provide Spanish food homely prepared by locals at their own houses, where you would taste it in complete privacy.</p><p>After lunch, you can cross the Triana Bridge in pure ?8 Basque Surnames? movie style, stroll along the river to the <a href=\\"#oro\\"><strong>Torre del Oro</strong></a> (see if you can spot a pirate ship :) and continue towards the center, where you?ll find <a href=\\"#constitucion\\"><strong>Avenida de la Constitución</strong></a>, the location where the movie ?Knight and Day? with Tom Cruise and Cameron Diaz was filmed. However, unlike the movie, don?t expect to find bulls roaming the streets; for that, it?s better to head to Pamplona.</p><p>For dinner time, we head over to the area of the <a href=\\"#setas\\"><strong>Metropol Parasol (Las Setas)</strong></a>, where the movie ?The Motive? was filmed. In this area, you can enjoy some tapas at <a href=\\"#palo\\"><strong>Palo Cortao</strong></a>, or if you?re looking for something more chic, you can visit the terrace of the <a href=\\"#unuk\\"><strong>Unuk Hotel</strong></a>, where you can stay for a drink afterwards with incredible views.</p><p>If you want to extend the night, you can end up at the <a href=\\"#koko\\"><strong>Koko</strong></a> nightclub. Alternatively, if you prefer something quieter and more bohemian, the <a href=\\"#alameda\\"><strong>Alameda de Hércules</strong></a> is a great place with plenty of terraces to enjoy a cocktail or some beers. For example, you can visit <a href=\\"#eureka\\"><strong>Café Bar Eureka</strong></a>.</p>                	<p>On day 2, you can start at <a href=\\"#luisa\\"><strong>María Luisa Park</strong></a>, not only one of the most beautiful parks in the city, but also the location of Plaza América and <a href=\\"#espana\\"><strong>Plaza España</strong></a>, which has been the backdrop for great films like Star Wars, The Dictator, and Lawrence of Arabia. Plaza de España is a dreamlike setting, a place where dreams take shape in bright tiles and water that reflects the faces of those who walk through it. In every corner, in every architectural detail, you can breathe in the art and history of the city.</p><p>Next, you can head towards the area where ?Carmen,? the quintessential literary work ?Carmen the Cigar Maker,? was filmed, telling the story of 19th-century Seville. To do this, you should visit the old Tobacco Factory, now known as ?<a href=\\"#rectorado\\"><strong>El Rectorado</strong></a>.? El Rectorado was built in the 18th century and originally served as the headquarters of the Royal Seminary College of San Telmo, an educational institution for priestly formation. Later, in 1845, after Mendizábal?s disentailment, the building passed into the hands of the state and became the headquarters of the University of Seville. Today, it is a public building, but it?s worth exploring the surroundings and admire the famous <a href=\\"#alfonso\\"><strong>Alfonso XIII Hotel</strong></a>, several times set of the well-known series ?The Crown?.</p><p>After this eventful morning, you can take a break and grab a bite to eat at <a href=\\"#teresas\\"><strong>Las Teresas</strong></a>, which is a classic spot in the area, or at the bar <a href=\\"#ovejas\\"><strong>Ovejas Negras</strong></a>.</p><p>Then, we?ll head to <a href=\\"#pilatos\\"><strong>Casa Pilatos</strong></a> (closes at 6 PM), set of the films ?Kingdom of Heaven? starring Orlando Bloom or ?1492: The Conquest of Paradise?, by the same director, Ridley Scott, and afterwards, you can stay in the Santa Cruz neighborhood, where you?ll find remnants of medieval Seville. It?s a place filled with legends and mysteries. Its narrow, dark alleyways have been the backdrop for stories intertwined with Sevillian folklore. The streets even served as the setting for the film ?Nobody Knows Anybody? with Eduardo Noriega, set against the backdrop of Seville?s Holy Week. In this area, if you?re in the mood for a flamenco show, I recommend <a href=\\"#flamenco\\"><strong>La Casa del Flamenco</strong></a> for a very comprehensive performance.</p><p>As night falls, the city transforms into a spectacle of lights and shadows. The narrow streets fill with music, and flamenco echoes in the air, like the soundtrack of a movie. For dinner in the area, you can treat yourself at the <a href=\\"#marco\\"><strong>San Marco Santa Cruz restaurant</strong></a>, located in 12th-century Arab baths, and then have a drink on the terrace of the <a href=\\"#bribon\\"><strong>Bribón</strong></a> bar by the river, which has a lively atmosphere at night.</p>                	<p>On the third day, if you have time, you must visit the <a href=\\"#italica\\"><strong>Ruins of Itálica</strong></a>, known as Pozo Dragón in the seventh and eighth seasons of Game of Thrones, serving as the backdrop for some of the series? most epic scenes. While you?re in Santiponce, don?t forget to visit the <a href=\\"#isidoro\\"><strong>Monastery of San Isidoro del Campo</strong></a> (except on Mondays when it?s closed), where a scene from the movie ?Alatriste? was filmed, specifically the one where he meets the Grand Inquisitor.</p><p>For lunch in the area, if you don?t have time to return to Seville, I recommend <a href=\\"#canario\\"><strong>Ventorrillo Canario</strong></a>, known for its grilled meats. One of the most well-known scenes from ?Alatriste? that came to life on the streets of Seville was filmed at the <a href=\\"#caridad\\"><strong>Hospital de la Caridad</strong></a>, which you shouldn?t miss, or the scene at the Casa de la Moneda theater (unfortunately, not open to the public).</p><p>To bid farewell to Seville, we can?t miss the obligatory visit to the <a href=\\"#alcazar\\"><strong>Real Alcázar</strong></a>, known as the ?Palace of the Kingdom of Dorne? in Game of Thrones. A visit to the Alcázar of Seville is like stepping into a period film, where architecture, lush gardens, and history converge into a visually stunning experience.</p><p>The camera starts rolling in the Courtyard of the Maidens, where Moorish-style tiles tell a tale of Islamic and Mudéjar influences. The intricately carved columns and delicately adorned arches are like the stars of this opening scene. Every corner is a work of art in itself, where light filters through the lattice work. The sound of water in the fountains and ponds adds a serene soundtrack to the scene. The Gardens of Mercury and the Ladies are like natural sets that frame this film.</p><p>For dinner in the area, I recommend the bar <a href=\\"#morales\\"><strong>Casa Morales</strong></a> for a more authentic and Sevillian experience, and if you?re in the mood for a more sophisticated restaurant, be sure to visit the <a href=\\"#fernando\\"><strong>San Fernando restaurant</strong></a> and get into the Alfonso XIII Hotel (I recommend making a reservation in advance to ensure availability).</p><p>Enjoy!</p>\t\t	373	pexels-sami-abdullah-7359476.jpg	1147,1148,1149,1150,1151,1152,1153,1154,1155	14.9	15.65	70069.40	S	en	2,92,269,12,263,260,102,266,252,126,257,138,250,14,21,153,168,132,69,242,9,131,123,256,264,265,147,8,166	&lt;iframe src=\\"https://www.google.com/maps/d/u/2/embed?mid=1bD9obS20izmEvVcT_eoFXbT6yb9HqyU&ehbc=2E312F&noprof=1\\" width=\\"640\\" height=\\"480\\"&gt;	prod_QuHt9ZB9kXAffl	price_1Q2TJpAFILSEnUZX9O6hvzJV	1	N	N	Discover Seville as if you were in a movie	\N	\N	Movie Sets	prod_Qv1GExqa7WZ5dn	price_1Q3BERAFILSEnUZXgrFfyfow		https://buy.stripe.com/test_eVadTZ0cJ7BY5AQ2d2		plink_1Q3BIaAFILSEnUZXG6bBVC0y	3Dias	10	N
374	S	anonimo	2024-09-23 17:10:26	2024-11-22 07:10:26	11357	2023-10-01 00:00:00	SV12 Rooftops 3 days	Panoramic and Fascinating Views	panoramic-and-fascinating-views	<strong><span style=\\"color: #ff008c;\\">Discover the Trendy Rooftop Terraces Frequented by Sevillians and Discover the City from Its Highest Points</span></strong>\\r\\n\\r\\n<span style=\\"font-weight: 400;\\">An unparalleled experience that blends history, gastronomy, and breathtaking views. Explore viewpoints, savor delicious local cuisine, and dine on terraces with stunning panoramas. Discover historic sites, stroll along the river, enjoy museums, and parks. This adventure immerses you in the essence of Sevilla, providing a captivating perspective on its rich culture and flavors.</span>	10	Hotel-Palacio-Alcazar.jpg	1	<p>We begin our visit to Seville at the <a href=\\"#setas\\"><strong>Metropol Parasol</strong></a>, known as ?Las Setas,? which will be our first 360° viewpoint from where we can see the entire city from above.</p><p>We continue along Imagen Street until we reach <a href=\\"#duque\\"><strong>Plaza del Duque</strong></a>, where we?ll ascend to the terrace of El Corte Inglés to enjoy lunch at <a href=\\"#manolo\\"><strong>Manolo León Plaza del Duque</strong></a> (reservation required). Their oxtail will leave you impressed, and they also offer excellent meats, but their crispy artichokes are not to be overlooked. Afterward, don?t miss trying one of <a href=\\"#manu\\"><strong>Manu Jara?s</strong></a> desserts inside El Corte Inglés (Plaza del Duque).</p><p>If you?re looking for a more immersive experience, one option I recommend for dining today or any other day is to try <a style=\\"color: #f41b8c; text-decoration: underline;\\" href=\\"#sazon\\"><b style=\\"font-family: var(--global-body-font-family);\\">SAZÓN The Folk Cook</b></a>, SAZON is the world\\ s first platform to provide Spanish food homely prepared by locals at their own houses, where you would taste it in complete privacy.</p><p>With satisfied stomachs, we take <a href=\\"#pellon\\"><strong>Puente y Pellón</strong></a> Street, then continue on Lineros Street until we reach Francos Street, immersing ourselves in the heart of the Santa Cruz neighborhood. Well-known spots like <a href=\\"#plazasantacruz\\"><strong>Plaza de Santa Cruz</strong></a>, Plaza de los Venerables, or Callejón del Agua transport us to a Seville of another era.</p><p>Calle del Agua leads us to the <a href=\\"#patio\\"><strong>Patio de Banderas</strong></a>, and once we exit to Plaza del Triunfo, we?ll head to the entrance of the <a href=\\"#alcazar\\"><strong>Royal Alcazars of Seville</strong></a> (make sure to buy your ticket in advance). After the visit, where you?ll take your time exploring its rooms and strolling through its gardens, we head to Mateos Gago Street to enjoy some delicious tapas for dinner. You can do this in one bar or go from bar to bar trying different tapas with a cold beer. A special mention goes to <a href=\\"#columnas\\"><strong>Bar Santa Cruz ?Las Columnas</strong></a>,? where you mustn?t miss trying their shredded meat sandwich (montadito de pringá) or their Russian salad.</p><p>To welcome the night, we?ll go up to the terrace of <a href=\\"#donamaria\\"><strong>Hotel Doña Maria</strong></a>, where the Giralda will be another guest at our table while we enjoy a cocktail or a mixed drink. Of course, you can also order wines or beers.</p>                	<p>Today we?re going to a different area. We head towards <a href=\\"#constitucion\\"><strong>Avenida de la Constitución</strong></a>, starting from Puerta de Jerez (but be careful with the tram!), and walk to the <a href=\\"#catedral\\"><strong>Cathedral</strong></a> for a visit (make sure to get your ticket in advance).</p><p>Once you exit through <a href=\\"#triunfo\\"><strong>Plaza del Triunfo</strong></a>, return to Constitution Avenue and look up to enjoy the impressive and distinct facades you?ll encounter. The most striking, before reaching the cathedral, is the recently renovated <a href=\\"#moneda\\"><strong>Royal Mint building</strong></a>. Right across, you?ll find the hidden section within the building?s wall that, if you pay attention, marks where the city wall used to be. We continue towards the river to the majestic <a href=\\"#oro\\"><strong>Torre del Oro</strong></a>, sentinel of the city.</p><p>Once here, we offer you two options: take one of the panoramic cruises (for example, <a href=\\"#cruise\\"><strong>Torre del Oro Cruises</strong></a>) available in the area, or stroll along the riverside to the Triana Bridge, taking beautiful photos with the bridge, Calle Betis, or Torre del Oro in the background. Don?t worry, it?s easily accessible.</p><p>After crossing the bridge and arriving at the typical Altozano Square, where Calle Betis begins, we?ll stop for lunch at <a href=\\"#betis7\\"><strong>Betis7</strong></a> restaurant. We recommend trying their truffled potatoes, salmon tartare, or deer sirloin. Another option with spectacular views is the terrace at <a href=\\"#trifulca\\"><strong>Maria Trifulca</strong></a>.</p><p>In the afternoon, we head to Plaza Nueva where we find the <a href=\\"#ayto\\"><strong>city hall</strong></a>. Behind it, we?ll ascend to Plaza del Salvador, where the majestic <a href=\\"#salvador\\"><strong>Church of El Salvador</strong></a> stands. <strong>IMPORTANT TIP</strong>: If you haven?t purchased the ticket for the cathedral and the line is unbearable, the ticket is joint with El Salvador, and you can buy it here to visit both.</p><p>Once we exit, we?re going to <a href=\\"#puravida\\"><strong>Pura Vida</strong></a> terrace for dinner with cocktails and incredible city views. Try their pornstar prawns or octopus salad. Some nights, they have performances on their terrace, so be sure to make a reservation.</p><p>If you want to extend the night, and it?s a weekend (Thursday, Friday, or Saturday), my personal advice is to have a drink on the <a href=\\"#lobby\\"><strong>Lobby</strong> <strong>terrace</strong></a>. The views are opposite to what we usually have in our memory.</p>                	<p>Our last day on this route through Seville from the heights, I recommend visiting the <a href=\\"#bellas\\"><strong>Fine Arts Museum</strong></a>, located in Museum Square. Admission is free for Europeans. Housed in a former Mercedarian monastery, it holds works by Velázquez, Murillo, and Zurbarán.</p><p>To eat, we?ll head to the bustling <a style=\\"color: #f41b8c;\\" href=\\"#alameda\\"><strong>Alameda de Hércules</strong></a>. We have various options to choose from, including national, international, and fusion cuisines. However, our recommendation is The Corner House Urban Hotel, which features a beautiful restaurant with a terrace called <a href=\\"#disparate\\"><strong>El Disparate</strong></a>. They offer an exquisite menu, with standout dishes like aged beef carpaccio and sunny-side-up eggs, along with an excellent cocktail selection.</p><p>After our meal, we?ll make our way to the quintessential city viewpoint terrace at <a href=\\"#atalaya\\"><strong>the Torre Sevilla Hotel (Atalaya)</strong></a>. In case you?re arriving by car, there?s a parking facility underneath the shopping center where you can park for free for up to 3 hours.</p><p>To bid farewell to Seville, we?ll head to the only area we haven?t yet explored?the <a href=\\"#luisa\\"><strong>Maria Luisa Park</strong></a>, its gardens, and the Plaza de España. Here, we?ll enjoy one last beer or cocktail on one of the terraces we find. Let?s raise a toast one last time to these wonderful days in the city, with a fresh perspective from up high.</p><p>If you need a place to dine in this area and want to treat yourselves one last time, two good options are <a href=\\"#ozama\\"><strong>Casa Ozama</strong></a> or <a href=\\"#riogrande\\"><strong>Rio Grande</strong></a>. And If you want to have a drink, <a href=\\"#muelle\\"><strong>Muelle de Nueva York</strong></a> is a very good option, or <a href=\\"#embarcadero\\"><strong>El Embarcadero</strong></a>. </p><p>I recommend booking restaurants in advance whenever possible to ensure availability, and also checking opening hours. You can adjust the order based on the route you?re taking. I hope you enjoy it!</p><p>I trust you?ve enjoyed these three days and that you?ll cherish a great memory of your experience.</p><p>See you soon!</p>\t\t	374	Hotel-Palacio-Alcazar.jpg	1156,1157,1158,1159,1160,1161,1162	14.9	15.65	70069.40	S	en	2,297,92,280,288,170,291,281,75,109,153,293,273,274,168,142,301,145,272,284,276,88,232,123,285,277,8,290,294,283,166,287	&lt;iframe src=\\"https://www.google.com/maps/d/u/2/embed?mid=1oNBuatLI6CTsuS-YTC1Z1XlDyCi7fV4&ehbc=2E312F&noprof=1\\" width=\\"640\\" height=\\"480\\"&gt;	prod_QuHtuXHtncbWuz	price_1Q2TJqAFILSEnUZXEeqjg6Oe	1	N	N	Discover the Trendy Rooftop Terraces Frequented by Sevillians and Discover the City from Its Highest Points	\N	\N	Panoramic and Fascinating Views	prod_QuosJp96bII2S0	price_1Q2zF3AFILSEnUZXnaQJAdk0		https://buy.stripe.com/test_5kA8zF5x3bSe8N27v6		plink_1Q3AnlAFILSEnUZXnEv9tDN3	3Dias	11	N
572	S	anonimo	2024-11-15 00:03:14	2024-11-22 07:10:33	28427	2024-11-15 00:00:00	MED SHOPPING 1 DAY	Shopping y moda 1 Dia	shopping-y-moda-1-dia	<strong><span style=\\"color: #ff008c;\\">Disfruta de la ruta de tiendas más \\"Fashion\\" de Medellín</span></strong>\\r\\n\\r\\n<span style=\\"font-weight: 400;\\">Disfrute de esta ruta para los apasionados del shopping y la moda en la ciudad de la eterna primavera, conozca a diseñadores de moda independientes galardonados y comparta experiencias en sus propios entornos creativos, y visite algunos de los malls de compras mas recomendados de la ciudad. Y disfrute de nuestras recomendaciones gastronómicas para ponerle la guinda perfecta a su estancia.</span>	208	pexels-porapak-apichodilok-346751.jpg	4	<p>Welcome!! Medellín is recognized as the fashion capital in Colombia, in fact, in July of each year fashion week is held,  Fashion Colombia. A series of events are taking place this week in Medellín with designers, brands and relevant personalities from the industry in this country.<br /><br />At the beginning of the year in January, +500 exhibitors meet with +12 thousand buyers from Colombia and many countries around the world, to learn about the latest trends in textiles, machinery, supplies and specialized services at the Colombiatex fair .</p><p>Spend an inspiring few days in the area that is home to the most successful group of designers in the ever-expanding local independent fashion scene. From tailored suits to custom-made jewelry to unique feminine silhouettes, our selection of designers has often handled the entire look of pop stars, film actors and international entrepreneurs.</p><p>Today we invite you to visit some of the recommended stores and boutiques on this fashion and shopping route through Medellín. We started the plan in the morning in the Poblado area, my recommendations in the area are  <b><a style=\\"color: #f41b8c; text-decoration: underline;\\" href=\\"#onzas\\">40 Ounces</a> :</b> handmade jewelry and accessories <b>,</b> Lievre <b>:</b> pants with anatomical molding, smart textiles and responsible processes. Palmeramia <b>:</b> it is a fusion of streetwear and philanthropy, representing Miami and Medellín, with your purchase you help communities without drinking water in La Guajira, <b><a style=\\"color: #f41b8c; text-decoration: underline;\\" href=\\"#desatin\\">Desatin</a> :</b> They have clothes to live life on the go. If you don?t have almost time, but you want to go to a concept store that has almost everything in terms of Colombian fashion and design, you can?t miss going to  <b><a href=\\"#makeno\\">Makeno</a> .</b> If you prefer a brand with a Colombian heritage that creates 100% handmade leather garments using traditional techniques, don?t forget to stop by Andrea Landa <b>.</b></p><p>If you need to include furniture designed and manufactured in our country on your shopping list, stop by <b><a href=\\"#perceptual\\">Perceptual</a> ,</b> and don?t forget to go to 902 Showroom .</p><p>In the afternoon you can go shopping at a mall, for example we have <b><a style=\\"color: #f41b8c;\\" href=\\"#mayorca\\">Mayorca el Outlet</a> ,</b> Large shopping center with dozens of retail and discount stores, a movie theater, and a food court. either <a href=\\"#super\\"><b>Super Fashion Center</b></a> in Itagui. They have a large commercial and industrial space where fashion is the protagonist, warehouses with their own brands at the best prices.</p><p>If you are still in Mayorca, the recommended one for dinner is <b><a href=\\"#forno\\">Il forno</a> ,</b> Italian food for everyone. or if you prefer something healthier,  <a href=\\"#mundo\\"><b>Green World</b></a>  is for you. They are the recipe for balance.  Breakfast, pet•friendly co-working, lunch or afternoon with friends ? all in one place</p><p>At dinner time, if you are a fan of chicharron and continue through the Itaguin sector, you cannot leave without trying Porcheta, in <b><a href=\\"#kamaos\\">Kamaos</a> ,</b> a true experience of flavors, located in the Simon Bolivar Park of Itagui.</p>\t\t	\N	\N	572	\N	\N	6.9			N	en	1821,1835,1836,4535,1823,1832,1824,1833,1834	&lt;iframe src=\\"https://www.google.com/maps/d/u/4/embed?mid=1LUO3Vd8QrDOdmlbAaeigDQ4R31mNC7Y&ehbc=2E312F&noprof=1\\" width=\\"640\\" height=\\"480\\"&gt;	\N	\N	\N	N	N	Disfruta de la ruta de tiendas más \\"Fashion\\" de Medellín	\N	\N	Shopping y moda 1 Dí­a							1Dia	209	N
376	S	anonimo	2024-09-23 17:10:51	2024-11-22 07:10:26	14303	2023-09-27 00:00:00	MAD01ART MODERNO	Arte Contemporáneo	arte-contemporaneo	<strong>\\r\\n<span style=\\"color: #ff008c;\\">Una experiencia inolvidable de arte contemporáneo</span>\\r\\n</strong>\\r\\n\\r\\n<span style=\\"font-weight: 400;\\">Embárquese en un viaje inolvidable por el mundo del arte contemporáneo en los vibrantes barrios de Chueca, Las Letras y Lavapiés. Sumérjase en 3 días de maravillas artísticas, en los que explorará acogedoras galerías y encontrará cautivadoras exposiciones. Pasee tranquilamente por encantadoras calles y relájese en pintorescos parques, mientras saborea la esencia de estos barrios únicos. Disfrute de la oportunidad de relajarse en cafés y bares que ofrecen un ambiente distintivo y acogedor. Esta es su oportunidad de crear recuerdos duraderos y sumergirse en el rico tapiz de la escena artística contemporánea de Madrid.</span>	12	foto-arte-moderno.jpg	2	<p>La primera parada la podréis hacer tomando algo en el espacio de arte <a href=\\"#macanudobar\\"><strong>MacanudoS</strong></a> . Te sugiero que vayas a <a href=\\"#fourquetstreet\\"><strong>la calle Fourquet</strong></a> que es nuestra calle de referencia, ya que es la que tiene más galerías por kilómetro cuadrado.</p><p>En los puntos de interés detallo los que más nos gustan. Todas son galerías muy pequeñas y el trato es casi personalizado. Siempre puede encontrar esculturas, fotografía, arte contemporáneo o de vanguardia. Cada cierto tiempo cambian.</p><p>El ambiente en la calle Fourquet es bastante especial, en todos los bares se pueden mantener conversaciones muy interesantes sobre las obras de las galerías.</p><p>En la zona recomiendo comer o tomar un brunch en <a href=\\"#carmencitabrunchlavapies\\"><strong>Carmencita Brunch Lavapiés</strong></a>. Para una cerveza tiene <a href=\\"#tabernalachulapademayrit\\"><strong>Taberna la chulapa en mayrit</strong></a> donde hacen una deliciosa tortilla de patatas y torreznos. La zona de Lavapiés es especial, por lo que pasear por ella es interesante. Hay un parque <strong><a style=\\"color: #f41b8c; text-decoration: underline;\\" href=\\"#estoesunaplaza\\">Esta es una plaza</a></strong> donde se puede caminar o leer, un oasis en medio del caos de la capital. Tienes en la misma calle varios lugares para tomar un café, los que más nos gustan son: para tomar un café <a href=\\"#hellocoffeefourquet\\"><strong>Hola Coffee Fourquet</strong></a> . Para cenar te sugiero <a href=\\"#lalorenza\\"><strong>La Lorenza</strong></a> que es uno de los mejores de la zona o <a href=\\"#eleconomico\\"><strong>El Económico</strong></a> , este último es un bar de los de siempre.</p>                	<p>Hoy sugiero comenzar por ?<a href=\\"#lacasaencendida\\"><strong>La casa encendida</strong></a>? , donde hay varias exposiciones y además hay una bonita cafeteria muy interesante de conocer. También debería ir a la <a href=\\"#barriodechueca\\"><strong>zona de Chueca </strong></a>donde hay varias galerías como <strong><a style=\\"color: #f41b8c; text-decoration: underline;\\" href=\\"#madismad\\">Mad Is Mad</a></strong>, <a href=\\"#yellowkorner\\"><strong>Yellowkorner</strong></a> si te gusta la fotografía. Mis recomendaciones para comer son <a href=\\"#trattoriapulcinella\\"><strong>Trattoria Pulcinella</strong></a> y nuestro favorito <a href=\\"#lamordida\\"><strong>La mordida</strong></a>. También puede entrar en <a href=\\"#faraday\\"><strong>Faraday</strong></a> a tomar un café y si te gustan las cosas vintage, ver su tienda de discos de vinilo y probar su tarta de limón y lavanda. En Chueca nos encanta el ambiente por lo que cualquier rincón es perfecto para sentarse a escuchar un concierto, comer o disfrutar, la Plaza Pedro Zerolo suele tener muy buen ambiente. Para cenar recomiendo si quiere algo tranquilo el restaurante <a href=\\"#los33\\"><strong>Los 33</strong></a>.</p>                	<p>Hoy propongo pasear por la <a href=\\"#barriodehuertas\\"><strong>Zona de Huertas</strong>,</a> almorzar en <a href=\\"#matilda\\"><strong>Matilda</strong></a> y ver galerías de arte moderno muy interesantes como<a href=\\"#thegoma\\"> <strong>Goma </strong></a>o <a href=\\"#malvingallery\\"><strong>Galería Malvín</strong></a>. Otro plan interesante es pasar la mañana en el <a href=\\"#reinasofia\\"><strong>Reina Sofía</strong></a> y tomar un brunch en <a href=\\"#orishasrestaurante\\"><strong>el Restaurante Orishas</strong></a> . Si vas a las Huertas, paseas por la zona y descubres sus rincones, entra en la <strong><a style=\\"color: #f41b8c; text-decoration: underline;\\" href=\\"#gulliver\\">Librería Gulliver</a></strong> de la calle León.</p><p>Para un aperitivo le sugiero que vaya al <a href=\\"#antonmartin\\"><strong>Antón Martin mercado</strong></a> el puesto de Donde Sanchez es perfecto para tomar un vermut o un vino y me encanta Pepin Lorite para comer algo de pescado. </p><p> Para la tarde te sugiero <a href=\\"#tabernaalsurdehuertas\\"><strong>La Taberna El Sur de Huertas</strong></a> . </p><p>Toda la parte trasera del Reina Sofía es una zona muy multicultural, así que pasear por allí es muy buena opción. Si te gusta la gastronomía india tienes <a href=\\"#calcuta\\"><strong>Calcuta</strong></a> en la calle Lavapiés y por la noche puedes ir al mercado de la cebada y tomar un cóctel en <a href=\\"#elviajero\\"><strong>El Viajero</strong></a> .</p><p>Espero que os guste y espero veros muchas veces más.</p><p>¡Que aproveche!</p>\t\t	376	foto-arte-moderno.jpg	1173,1174,1175,1176,1177,1178,1179,1180,1181,1182,1183	14.9	15.65	70069.40	S	es	338,354,363,339,340,347,345,364,352,343,346,344,351,360,353,348,357,355,361,358,342,359,362,341,356,350,349	&lt;iframe src=\\"https://www.google.com/maps/d/u/2/embed?mid=1lCZya90xDXx4VeH7-rVqAg8lX6eD83g&ehbc=2E312F&noprof=1\\" width=\\"640\\" height=\\"480\\"&gt;	prod_QuHtIXhoFIUm0y	price_1Q2TJrAFILSEnUZXMczhBHiK	1	S	S	Una experiencia inolvidable de arte contemporáneo	\N	\N	Arte Con